(436, 376, '_panels_data_preview', 'a:3:{s:7:\"widgets\";a:1:{i:0;a:6:{s:5:\"title\";s:0:\"\";s:4:\"text\";s:12467:\"<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><strong>Information about organizations:</strong></span></p><ul style=\"text-align: justify;\"><li><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><strong><u>Syrian Education Commission</u></strong>:This is a non-profit, non-political civil society organization that is specialized in the educational process in all its stages. It takes cares of the Syrian students by monitoring and seeking solutions for them through values such as teamwork, originality and modernity, credibility and transparency and professional standards. They have created many projects but the one that we visited was the “Project of Dropout Pupils”, which consists in establishing centers in Turkey for educating and rehabilitating students who have been deprived of education in order to prevent them from wandering in the streets and getting lost in the mazes of ignorance and terrorism.</span></li><li><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><u><strong>ASAM (Istanbul’s unit)</strong>:</u> The Association for Solidarity with Asylum Seekers and Migrants (ASAM) was established in Ankara on December 22, 1995 as a non-profit and non-governmental organization. The primary goal of ASAM is to create solutions to the problems that refugees and asylum seekers encounter in Turkey, to help them to fulfill their primary needs and to support them to provide access for fundamental rights and services. ASAM provides services to refugees and asylum seekers without discrimination on the grounds of language, religion, sex, race, sexual orientation and political ideology.(Veronica, UWCM\'17)</span></li></ul><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW12.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-383\"><img class=\"wp-image-383 size-large aligncenter\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW12-1024x683.jpg\" alt=\"PW12\" width=\"700\" height=\"467\" /></a></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW14.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-381\"><img class=\"wp-image-381 size-large aligncenter\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW14-1024x576.jpg\" alt=\"PW14\" width=\"700\" height=\"394\" /></a></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><strong>Why this project week?</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">We chose this project week for couple of reasons. The first one is the activity, which is helping Syrian refugees. As we all know, many Syrians left their country, which is in a situation of a brutal civil war, in order to start their life again. We felt obligated to help them, and especially the kids, who are the next generation. Another reason is the location. Many people assume that Turkey is not a safe place because of what they hear in the media. We wanted to go there in order to see what Turkey is really is, and it turned out to be one of the most welcoming places we have ever been to! Despite the media, Turkey is safe, Istanbul is safe, and it was important to prove that.</span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">(Achiad, UWCM’16)</span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW11.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-384\"><img class=\"wp-image-384 size-large aligncenter\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW11-1024x576.jpg\" alt=\"PW11\" width=\"700\" height=\"394\" /></a></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><strong>One of our day : </strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Thursday 11th of February</span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Day four.</span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">This day was our second day in the organisation “ Al Asam”.</span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">We left our apartment that is in the area of Sultan Ahmet at approximately 9 o\'clock to go to Karaköy.</span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">From that point we had to walk more than one hour. It was really difficult because the city is like a mountain and we do need to climb especially the way we had taken that day.</span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">We arrived to the organisation at around 10 and there was a Turkish lesson for the children (3 to 8 years old). We joined the lesson and helped the children with memorising exercise.</span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">After the end of the lesson we had a lot of fun activities with them and this was the most important and enjoying moment of the journey.</span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">At 3 o\'clock the second group of students came. They were mainly teenagers and with a highest age of 15. The day before we have gone with them near to the sea for their photography lesson.</span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">That day they had hip hop dance and singing lesson. The teachers were really professional and they danced very well. We also joined the dance lesson. And we had fun. The day before during the way to the sea they have taught us some Arabic and we taught them our first languages.</span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">At the end of the dance lesson was the singing lesson. Each of the teenagers had their own lyrics that they sing to express what they cannot say through music. We also participated to that lesson by doing random freestyle on a bit.</span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">At the end of the day we had an exchanges of addresses with them to keep being in touch.</span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">(Naimatou, UWCM’17)</span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW15.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-380\"><img class=\"wp-image-380 size-large aligncenter\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW15-1024x681.jpg\" alt=\"PW15\" width=\"700\" height=\"466\" /></a></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><strong>Our objectives :</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Our learning goals and objectives are to build project planning skills through the organization of the project week, build communication skills through the contact with Syrian organizations, become more aware of the situation of the Syrian children in foreign countries and have an impact on them through our own effort. During the project week in Istanbul we achieved our learning goals and objectives fully. Meanwhile, we planned the trip in Turkey entirely on our own: we booked the flight tickets, apartments and navigated ourselves to different locations, while everything went on smoothly. Also, we had a very good time with both organizations we worked with. We contacted them beforehand and arrived on time. They were very welcoming and there was no miscommunication within the process. Sitting together with Syrian kids from different age groups in the same room, we had a great opportunity to interact with them closely and understand them better. Although there were huge language barriers among us, as we couldn’t speak arabic nor turkish, they didn’t stop us from being friends with those innocent, cheerful kids. At the end of the day we became from very close to one another and too hard to say goodbye. However, despite the fact that we enjoyed a lot working with the organization, we did identify several problems and difficult that the Syrian refugees encountered. A lot of them are suffering from poverty, because of their family inability to make a living, the kids themselves have to work by selling tissues to pedestrians. Though the organizations provide basic education for them, they don’t have money for textbooks and the basic educational resources. For them education is a luxury. We felt very sad about that and through the speech we gave them, and all the games we played with them, we hoped that they would never give up their hope and dreams and thrive with the help of education.</span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">(Nina, UWCM’17)</span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW17.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-378\"><img class=\"wp-image-378 size-large aligncenter\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW17-1024x681.jpg\" alt=\"PW17\" width=\"700\" height=\"466\" /></a></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW18.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-377\"><img class=\"wp-image-377 size-large aligncenter\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW18-1024x681.jpg\" alt=\"PW18\" width=\"700\" height=\"466\" /></a></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><strong>The importance of this Project Week :<em>                  </em></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">We headed to Turkey to help with the syrian refugees. The trip there was a challenge, because a lot of us come from priviledged backgrounds. We learned that the world is far from ideal and that there is a long way to go. However we all believed that if we fight and if we taught the children to fight as well for everyone’s rights, the world will become a better place. Staying with the children was a personal challenge because of the language barrier, which was interesting because as much as we were different we were still able to comprehend each other and to build a special relationship. Also, dealing with children and seeing them facing a such situation where they flee from their home and have to find a way to survive in the street made us sad, angry and more compassionate towards the cause. But we were there, we showed them support and even if they were young and might not have ununderstood why we left so early, at least we made them smile and this wasn’t the kind of smiles you can see in Western Europe. These were pure smiles that you cannot immitate. As bad as their situation can be, you can still see the way they are interested by anything and the happiness they can share with you. I think this project week was definitely important for each of us in the sense that we directly saw what we used to hear on the TV, medias, internet and that it changed somehow our mind. We all come from different countries and for some of us, going in Turkey with such a different culture than where we are from was eye opening to the similarities and differences that western and eastern cultures can have. The fact that one paraguayan, one guatemalan, two french, one moroccan, one egyptian, one burkinabe, one israeli and one chinese show that it is possible to help and that it is not that complicated to help people different from us.</span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">(Mathilde, UWCM’17)</span></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW16.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-379\"><img class=\"wp-image-379 size-large aligncenter\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW16-1024x681.jpg\" alt=\"PW16\" width=\"700\" height=\"466\" /></a></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">This project week lasted four days, but our actions won’t stop there. We come from all over the world and with this experience we can continue, at even bigger scales, to help</span>.</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">The refugee crisis is not a joke and media don’t share everything, so it’s our own responsibility to decide whether or not we should try to save people who die or children who are losing their childhood</span>.</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW13.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-382\"><img class=\"wp-image-382 size-large\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW13-1024x683.jpg\" alt=\"PW13\" width=\"700\" height=\"467\" /></a></p>\";s:20:\"text_selected_editor\";s:7:\"tinymce\";s:5:\"autop\";b:1;s:12:\"_sow_form_id\";s:13:\"56e6dab5eed80\";s:11:\"panels_info\";a:5:{s:5:\"class\";s:31:\"SiteOrigin_Widget_Editor_Widget\";s:4:\"grid\";i:0;s:4:\"cell\";i:0;s:2:\"id\";i:0;s:5:\"style\";a:2:{s:27:\"background_image_attachment\";b:0;s:18:\"background_display\";s:4:\"tile\";}}}}s:5:\"grids\";a:1:{i:0;a:2:{s:5:\"cells\";i:1;s:5:\"style\";a:0:{}}}s:10:\"grid_cells\";a:1:{i:0;a:2:{s:4:\"grid\";i:0;s:6:\"weight\";i:1;}}}'),
