(10, 1, '2017-06-21 10:18:38', '2017-06-21 10:18:38', '<img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-716\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/20170302_134838-1.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2576px) 100vw, 2576px\" srcset=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/20170302_134838-1-300x225.jpg 300w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/20170302_134838-1-768x576.jpg 768w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/20170302_134838-1-1024x768.jpg 1024w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/20170302_134838-1.jpg 2576w\" alt=\"20170302_134838\" width=\"2576\" height=\"1932\" />\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThis is an art based project in Paris and we will explore the different arts in museums and street arts. It will also focus on how does the refugee crisis in Europe impact the newly created art (if there are any). We will interview one artists with different age group, and some the refugees. In our first day we visited museum ‘’Musee du Montmartre’’, according to the website it supposed to be an old museum but after we went there we could not find any art from the 16 or 17 century. Therefore, we counted it as a modern one. 20170302_134838 In our second day, we had to visit the second biggest and popular museum in Paris ‘’musee de orsay’’. But the challenge was in finding the way to get there. We took the Metro, but the wrong one. However, after we spend two hours to reach it, we also had to wait for almost one and half other hour in the line to get there. It was a very famous old museum and we got to see a lot of old art from many artiest French and non-French. We got more idea about art in Paris’s museums and about Paris itself. As every evening we were giving our self a chance to go out and explore Paris. We visiting some popular tourist places in Paris like the tower and the Notre dame cathedral. We used to visit museums every day, even the day we supposed to visit the artist and interview her. In the third day we interviewed the artiest and we recorded the interview. She was originally from Iran, but migrate to France 25 years ago, and she graduated from an art university in France. Today she is an art teacher and she has a small studio and she teaches in her own way, because there are many things she doesn’t agree with the other French way of teaching art. The questions were about her journey in the art field and what are the changes that she has realized in the Modern art and what are the challenges she faces as an artist in Paris. The interview was an open conversation that we recorded. 20170227_122535 In our last day, we visited the Louvre, and it was much huger than we expected. We saw so many old art from the 16th and 17th, but of course we couldn’t finish quarter of it. If we will give a summary about the different between the old and modern art and how technology influence the modern art in Paris. In the 16th and 17th most of the arts were a religious based art and most of them seemed to have the same colours. While the modern art have different ways of using the colours and the idea of exhibitions is much used. The arties said that she is also a singer, she 10 years ago she came up with an idea of painting while she is singing, and she wanted to spread it Paris and teach it for the new generation, but sadly she was not allowed to do it because there was no references for it. That is why she said ‘’ In Paris the mother of art city, they don’t allowed you to create any art, you just have to copy what was already there, and I don’t consider this as a modern art.’’ We also failed to find any street art in Paris, the government does not allowed that because they want to keep the city as historical as it is. We also asked the arties about refugee and how if there are any opportunities for them in the art field, but the answer was an expected. She said in Paris people don’t care how brave you are in your art work and idea unless you are from a developed countries like, America, Netherlands, and Italy….so on. Therefore, refugees here have no chances at all until now. She said ‘’ even me who came here 25 years ago, I got rejected from many chances because I am from Iran’’. One thing we did not like about Paris was the traffic, to some extent it was very risky and unorganised, people don’t care about the traffic light at all, even if it is time for walker to pass cars will still keep going. We also felt the city was resist somehow, in some areas we observed that there were only Arab people, and in other only black people. As there were so many homeless people everywhere. But the people in general were very nice and helpful, many people were advising us to be careful and to take care of our self and properties, and they were helping us to find our way. In conclusion, we learnt a lot from this project. We get to know each other more by dividing the work between us, each of us learned something new. For example Rabab learnt how to cook, Hoza and Len learned how to read physical maps. We learned about the refugee in the art field, some French cultures and a lot about art in the mother of art city. Some of us already planned their next project that will be focused on the refugee homeless in Paris. We faced so many challenges to achieve this project, but we were all patient and by encouraging each other we were able to make it.', 'Art In Paris', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', '10__trashed', '', '', '2017-06-23 09:04:52', '2017-06-23 09:04:52', '', 0, 'http://localhost/project_week/?p=10', 0, 'post', '', 0),
