 interview her. In the third day we interviewed the artiest and we recorded the interview. She was originally from Iran, but migrate to France 25 years ago, and she graduated from an art university in France. Today she is an art teacher and she has a small studio and she teaches in her own way, because there are many things she doesn’t agree with the other French way of teaching art. The questions were about her journey in the art field and what are the changes that she has realized in the Modern art and what are the challenges she faces as an artist in Paris. The interview was an open conversation that we recorded. 20170227_122535 In our last day, we visited the Louvre, and it was much huger than we expected. We saw so many old art from the 16th and 17th, but of course we couldn’t finish quarter of it. If we will give a summary about the different between the old and modern art and how technology influence the modern art in Paris. In the 16th and 17th most of the arts were a religious based art and most of them seemed to have the same colours. While the modern art have different ways of using the colours and the idea of exhibitions is much used. The arties said that she is also a singer, she 10 years ago she came up with an idea of painting while she is singing, and she wanted to spread it Paris and teach it for the new generation, but sadly she was not allowed to do it because there was no references for it. That is why she said ‘’ In Paris the mother of art city, they don’t allowed you to create any art, you just have to copy what was already there, and I don’t consider this as a modern art.’’ We also failed to find any street art in Paris, the government does not allowed that because they want to keep the city as historical as it is. We also asked the arties about refugee and how if there are any opportunities for them in the art field, but the answer was an expected. She said in Paris people don’t care how brave you are in your art work and idea unless you are 