(314, 1, '2016-02-23 14:57:05', '2016-02-23 14:57:05', '<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #333333;\">Our group, consisting of <u>Asbjoern Hansen, Emma Agnelli, Martijn Hatfield and Leandra </u><u>Ilkka</u>, chose to help out at the local organisation <b><i>Animals Faith</i></b>. The organisation provides dog training, grooming, veterinary assistance, lodging and a shelter. The organisation runs mostly through the help of volunteers, so we knew that our help would be valuable, and this influenced us in choosing this project. We had not heard of many existing Project Weeks concerning animals, and we believe that helping animals is of great importance in any community so this was also a learning experience for us to see how animals are treated in Maastricht.</span></div>\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #333333;\"><b><u> [spacer height=\"20px\"]These were our goals:</u></b></span></div>\n<div><span style=\"color: #333333;\">1. Design and pursue a student-led project.</span>\n<span style=\"color: #333333;\"> 2. Provide a service to an organization/community.</span>\n<span style=\"color: #333333;\"> 3. Organize activities outside the campus.</span>\n<span style=\"color: #333333;\"> 6. Improve your organization, communication and collaboration skills.</span>\n<span style=\"color: #333333;\"> 7. Get to know more about yourself and your group.</span>\n<span style=\"color: #333333;\"> 10. Learn new (practical) skills</span></div>\n<div>\n\n<span style=\"color: #333333;\">[spacer height=\"20px\"]</span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #333333;\">We believe that we did achieve all of these goals throughout the week.This was a general program of one of our Project Week days:</span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #333333;\">- Arrive at Animals Faith 9:00</span>\n<span style=\"color: #333333;\"> - Clean outside pens and refill water 9:00-9:30</span>\n<span style=\"color: #333333;\"> - Clean first two rows of pens inside (refill water, wash floor, dry floor, clean out poop) 9:30-10:30</span>\n<span style=\"color: #333333;\"> - Go for a walk with dogs 10:30-11:30</span>\n<span style=\"color: #333333;\"> - Clean last two rows of pens inside (refill water, wash floor, dry floor, clean out poop) 11:30-12:30</span>\n<span style=\"color: #333333;\"> - Wash bowls, Clean gutter, Take out poop bins 12:30- 13:00</span>\n<span style=\"color: #333333;\"> - Departure from Animals Faith 13:00</span>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #333333;\">[spacer height=\"20px\"]</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #333333;\">Our project week was important because the practical work we did has an effect on the whole life of an animal staying at that shelter. For example, if we did not clean their bowls sufficiently they could become sick and if we did not dry their pens well enough this could hurt their paws and make them very uncomfortable. Our Project Week links to the UWC values because we had to show intercultural understanding since the care of the animals differed to that of some of our cultures and we had to adjust to that. We also embodied personal responsibility and integrity as well as mutual responsibility and respect, since we were responsible for the well being of the animals and for completing our tasks well and efficiently. We also embodied compassion and service, since a big part of our project week was interacting with animals and the people who worked at the organisation, and compassion is a large part of animal care.</span></p>\n<span style=\"color: #333333;\">Here are some photos of our time at the shelter!</span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #333333;\">PHOTOS</span>\n\n[gallery columns=\"5\" ids=\"321,320,319,318,317\"]\n\n</div>\n<div><span style=\"color: #333333;\"><a style=\"color: #333333;\" href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/dfgdfgd.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-316\">\n</a></span></div>', 'Animals Faith Volunteering', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'animals-faith-volunteering', '', '', '2017-06-23 10:08:42', '2017-06-23 10:08:42', '', 0, 'http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/?p=314', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(335, 1, '2016-03-09 15:01:29', '2016-03-09 15:01:29', '<h3><strong><em><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><span style=\"color: #000000; text-decoration: underline;\"> - Why did you choose the project?</span></span></em></strong></h3>\n<blockquote>Freedom is a value, a term, a notion, a concept that we feel very comfortable about.</blockquote>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #333333;\">Right from the beginning of the school year, we’ve been told by our peers and teachers about the possibility of doing a project week as part of the exceptional UWC experience which we, UWC students all want to live to the fullest. We have always thought that  it was especially important for us to do our first project week in Ireland, since we’ve both had a big interest in exploring the cultural and social development, growth and dynamics of this country caused by its rich history with a very specific aim that this population has longed for decades; freedom. Freedom is a value, a term, a notion, a concept that we feel very comfortable about. We often like to throw loosely into our  UWC discussions, seldom thinking critically of what freedom really means to us, be it freedom of speech, freedom of education or perhaps even just the simplest version of freedom commonly known as the power or right to think, speak, act or think as on wants. Despite all of it being essentially correct in its very narrow definition our intention was to challenge this tricky privilege we often find ourselves forgetting of as we tend to take it for granted, believing that’s it’s been given to like an inborn trait,  in its ultimate righteousness, just like the color of our hair and eyes along with all the other features that have been passed onto us from our parents. The Freedom achieved by the Dubliners as a consequence of the events during the Easter Rising in 1916 holds a certain dose of spirit, fiery, mood that humanizes those who have the courage to cherish, grow and protect the liberty they’ve fought for so long , and that in fact is still the principle reason for some ongoing tensions in other parts of that country. But it was the brave population of Dublin that reminded us of its infinite significance and responsibilities that freedom brings to our lives.</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">[spacer height=\"10px\"]</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400; color: #000000;\">With our understandable ignorance of the city, its dynamics, the people and the historic burden and atmosphere still very sensible in the streets of Dublin and unspecified expectations, we happened to approach this project with a rather fresh and unprejudiced mindset which eventually allowed us to discover the culture and history of Dublin for ourselves, using our own varying senses, for ourselves. It was the direct interaction with the people of this city which in the end represent at least to a some degree the culture, the art, the history and hence the spirit of the city that originated from a conflict we decided to investigate.  We wanted to experience something outside the parameters of UWC, something more real, more ordinary, humane and perhaps even more authentic, and although our main goal for this project week was to investigate a conflict from a more scholastic point-of-view based on analysis that we are thought to do in our academics, we learned much more about the people, the importance of human-interactions, kindness, empathy towards one another, understanding  and humanity itself than we would have ever expected. Finally we understood that the root of all positive, negative and neutral historical decisions lays in the human complexities which we all have. On a final note, beyond the acquisition of new knowledge, new skills that we gained this project week evoked unknown thoughts in us which made us learn a lot of intriguing things about ourselves and our team members. This made it a very reflective and useful experience on many different levels which I think was what we were ultimately looking for in a project week and Irish history and culture definitely helped us fulfill this goal.</span></p>\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW-1.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-340\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-340 size-large\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW-1-1024x575.jpg\" alt=\"PW 1\" width=\"700\" height=\"393\" /></a>\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><em><strong><span style=\"color: #000000; text-decoration: underline;\">[spacer height=\"20px\"]- What were your learning goals and objectives? Did you achieve them?</span></strong></em></span>\n<ol>\n	<li><span style=\"font-weight: 400; color: #000000;\"> Design and pursue a student-led project.</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> Organize activities outside the campus.</span> </span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Explore a new country and culture.</span></span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> Improve your organization, communication and collaboration skills.</span></span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Get to know more about yourself and your group.</span></span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> Share and spread the UWC mission and values.</span></span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"font-weight: 400; color: #000000;\"> Learn new (practical) skills.</span></li>\n</ol>\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400; color: #000000;\">We seem to have achieved all of the pre-fixed goals and we are proud of our experience.</span>\n\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW2.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-339\"><img class=\"wp-image-339 size-large aligncenter\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW2-1024x575.jpg\" alt=\"PW2\" width=\"700\" height=\"393\" /></a>\n<h3><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><em><strong><span style=\"color: #000000; text-decoration: underline;\"> [spacer height=\"20px\"]- General program and a detailed itinerary of a day of your PW?</span></strong></em></span></h3>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Every morning we would wake up, have breakfast and get ready to take the bus to the city. We had our meetings with the organization and other supporters of our project in the morning, involving visiting museums, expositions and even Trinity College. We would have lunch around the city and in the evening we would have time to walk around the city and get to know it better. We had some problems with orientation at the beginning when walking from one place to the other around the city, however, in the end, we are proud to say we managed to have a general idea of the city center and where all the important reference locations were. In the evening/night we would either have dinner in the city or take the bus back to the apartment, where we would plan our next day in detail.</span></p>\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW3.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-338\"><img class=\"wp-image-338 size-large aligncenter\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW3-1024x683.jpg\" alt=\"PW3\" width=\"700\" height=\"467\" /></a>\n<h3><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><em><strong><span style=\"color: #000000; text-decoration: underline;\">[spacer height=\"20px\"]- Why was your PW important?</span></strong></em></span></h3>\n<blockquote>We learned a lot of skills related to being a more independent person that are inherently important.</blockquote>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #333333;\">You can consider this question in two ways. The first is, why was this PW important to individuals of the group? The second is: Why was this PW important to the general cause of the project, which was to find out more about a historically fascinating period of change and struggle in Irish <i> and</i> European History? To answer the first question. The answer is very simple, and even though I can only vouch for myself, but I’m going to assume  all the participants had a great time. For most of us, it was the first time travelling without our parents, and we learned a lot of skills related to being a more independent person that are inherently important. Not only did we gain skills, but (as cheesy as it will sound) going to a new country, where we was constantly forced to talk to people, we learned how amazing and how interesting people are. Perhaps it is in the good nature of the Irish folk, but we believe certain characteristics of kindness can be found in most places depending on how you search for them. This is a big thing we lacked in looking for in people and that we missed, but we believe we have regained it thanks to Ireland. Secondly, it is impossibly important to realize the relevance of studying such cases- for innumerable reasons. It is also impossible to measure this value however, that only 5 students will take away from learning about a conflict, perhaps awareness? perhaps the unlikelihood that it will be occurred from ourselves? It is impossible to say. Not to mention how important it is to learn about different conflicts- learning about people and stories and histories is so critical because only when we are knowledgeable and culturally aware enough can we claim that we have abilities such as conflict resolution which are fatally imperative in our lives.</span></p>\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW4.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-337\"><img class=\"wp-image-337 size-large aligncenter\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW4-1024x683.jpg\" alt=\"PW4\" width=\"700\" height=\"467\" /></a>\n<h3><em><strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline; color: #000000;\">[spacer height=\"20px\"] - How did your PW link to the </span><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><span style=\"color: #000000; text-decoration: underline;\">UWC</span></span><span style=\"text-decoration: underline; color: #000000;\"> mission and values?</span></strong></em></h3>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">We believe that our project week had a great connection with UWC’s missions and values because the project which we were investigating was hugely involved in <span style=\"color: #000000;\">understanding</span></span><span style=\"color: #000000;\"> of the  culture of Ireland and values that a country possesses. Therefore, we think that this relation could contribute to our knowledge in terms of global understanding, awareness of global and historical problems and possible solutions that could be reached.</span></p>\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW5.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-336\"><img class=\"wp-image-336 size-large aligncenter\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW5-1024x683.jpg\" alt=\"PW5\" width=\"700\" height=\"467\" /></a>\n\n&nbsp;', 'Dublin, Ireland', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'feb16-dublin-ireland', '', '', '2017-06-23 10:08:17', '2017-06-23 10:08:17', '', 0, 'http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/?p=335', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(343, 1, '2016-03-09 15:14:45', '2016-03-09 15:14:45', 'by Melody Lam and Sophia-Iris Komparki\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400; color: #000000;\">[spacer height=\"20px\"]To be fairly honest, this wasn’t the most amazing project week ever. I’ve never done one before but there is quite a lot of room for improvement. Even so, there were still a lot of memorable and enjoyable moments.</span></p>\n\n<blockquote>We chose Arsis because it is a non-governmental organization (NGO) that is not only supporting refugees but also specializing in the social support of youth that are in difficulty or even danger.</blockquote>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">We worked with <strong>Arsis</strong>, a Greek organization that provides refuge for asylum seekers while their legal status in Greece is being processed. Apart from providing accommodation, they also work with homeless people in Athens, providing them with food and blankets (i.e. basic necessities). The organization also receives non-monetary donations from the public and reorganizes them to give it to the people in need. These include food, clothes, toys, blankets and toiletries and a lot more.</span></p>\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/IMG_7178-1.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-392\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-392 size-large\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/IMG_7178-1-1024x768.jpg\" alt=\"IMG_7178 (1)\" width=\"700\" height=\"525\" /></a>\n\n&nbsp;\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">We chose Arsis because it is a non-governmental organization (NGO) that is not only supporting refugees but also specializing in the social support of youth that are in difficulty or even danger. Their vision is really inspiring as they strive to create a society with equal opportunities for everyone. Their work has been proven to have a huge impact in the society. They have helped so far thousands of families. This could be achieved thanks to the organization collaborating with a very big number of social entrepreneurs and volunteers.</span></p>\n\n<blockquote>The room was about the size half the floor. It transformed with from a messy junkyard of donations to an organized inventory!</blockquote>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">We did some sort of service with the organization each day. When we emailed the organization, we were told that we would be handing out food and clothing to homeless people and refugees. When we arrived the organization, they turned out to be fairly unorganized. Instead of doing what we were promised, we ended up re-organizing their inventory of donations. To be honest, we were not very satisfied at the start, but I believe this was a very special learning experience. So, basically what we did every day was that we would arrive the organization at 10, re-organize their inventory and leave at 4. We did the same thing for 4 days. I was amazed by how we successfully re-organized the whole inventory/storage room in 4 days! The room was about the size half the floor. It transformed with from a messy junkyard of donations to an organized inventory! WE ARE PROUD OF OURSELVES.</span></p>\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/IMG_7182.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-393\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-395 size-large\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/IMG_7182-1024x768.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"700\" height=\"525\" /></a>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/IMG_7234-e1457967230283.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-396\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-396 size-large\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/IMG_7234-e1457967230283-768x1024.jpg\" alt=\"IMG_7234\" width=\"700\" height=\"933\" /></a>\n\n&nbsp;\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #333333;\">This day was our second day in the organisation “Al Asam”. We left our apartment that is in the area of Sultan Ahmet at approximately 9 o\'clock to go to Karaköy. From that point we had to walk more than one hour. It was really difficult because the city is like a mountain and we do need to climb especially the way we had taken that day. We arrived to the organisation at around 10 and there was a Turkish lesson for the children (3 to 8 years old). We joined the lesson and helped the children with memorizing exercise. After the end of the lesson we had a lot of fun activities with them and this was the most important and enjoying moment of the journey. At 3 o\'clock the second group of students came. They were mainly teenagers and with a highest age of 15. The day before we have gone with them near to the sea for their photography lesson. That day they had hip hop dance and singing lesson. The teachers were really professional and they danced very well. We also joined the dance lesson. And we had fun. The day before during the way to the sea they have taught us some Arabic and we taught them our first languages. At the end of the dance lesson was the singing lesson. Each of the teenagers had their own lyrics that they sing to express what they cannot say through music. We also participated to that lesson by doing random freestyle on a bit. At the end of the day we had an exchanges of addresses with them to keep being in touch.</span></p>\n\n<blockquote>The gist of service isn’t just about how directly working with your target group and making their lives better, it’s about being compassionate and understanding.</blockquote>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400; color: #000000;\">Although this project week had a lot of things we did not anticipate, we still met our project week goals. We successfully organized a project week and cooperated smoothly with the organization! (We thought we were going to miss our flight.) This was an off-campus project week which gained us a lot of insight about the Greek community. Most of the staff were Greeks or spoke Greek. We also stayed with Sophia-Iris’ family and met some of her friends. We talked about how different our home countries were compared to Greece and shared stories during the night. We definitely were able to learn a lot more about ourselves when we are all alone and hands on doing a project without much supervision of elders. Though we were not specifically spreading the UWC vision with target groups directly, we experienced it on another level ourselves. As we were a really international group, we also attracted a lot of attention and shared a lot of our experiences with Sophia’s family and friends. This is in another way spreading the UWC mission and values.</span></p>\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/IMG_7325-e1457967316543.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-397\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-397 size-large\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/IMG_7325-e1457967316543-768x1024.jpg\" alt=\"IMG_7325\" width=\"700\" height=\"933\" /></a>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400; color: #000000;\">One of the mission and values of UWC is service and compassion. The gist of service isn’t just about how directly working with your target group and making their lives better, it’s about being compassionate and understanding. In this case, we have to understand that this organization needs help with their storage. The organization is not just the middle-man between we and our target group, they are also humans and they also need help.  Our work with the inventory speeds up their process of helping their target group. And I believe if we manage to understand why we are cleaning instead of giving food to the needy, we have illustrated the embraced and lived the true meaning of service.</span></p>', 'Athens, Greece', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'feb16-athens-greece', '', '', '2017-06-23 10:08:04', '2017-06-23 10:08:04', '', 0, 'http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/?p=343', 0, 'post', '', 0);
