(369, 1, '2016-03-14 09:12:06', '2016-03-14 09:12:06', 'by Ane, Lochlann, Isabella, Jule, Julius, Aru, Mikhail and Adithya\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><strong>[spacer height=\"20px\"]Norway</strong> - a socialist utopia? Often cited among the best countries to live in, as a force for gender equality and social justice politically, the scarcely populated country makes a frequent appearance in the media. From Bernie Sanders to Disney’s Frozen, it is easy to view this tiny, mountainous nation with high regards - yet actually living or experiencing such a culture bids a different understanding.</span></p>\n\n<blockquote>We found value in the kind of discussion, dilemmas and brainwork one seldom encounters in a homogeneous, monocultural group.</blockquote>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Our project week was proposed as an opportunity for acquaintance, self-reflection - a chance to get a firmer grasp of a term we use frequently, yet often in a hollow manner. An investigation of how efficient the ‘’Nordic model’’ is, we claimed, an investigation into the manner which Nordic countries, such as Norway are run. In order to discover the effects of the “welfare state” and “mixed economy” this people embraces so zealously, we ventured to the capital of Oslo in order to gain impressions from both organizations and the common being. Indeed, it was educational - yet these days were filled of so much more substance than so.</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Few from the group can say it made them “understand” the “Nordic model” more. Yet we found value in the kind of discussion, dilemmas and brainwork one seldom encounters in a homogeneous, monocultural group. If it did not evoke an understanding of the Nordic model, surely it set a flame to our understanding of the world, of cultures and their inner workings.</span></p>\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW8.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-372\"><img class=\"wp-image-372 size-large aligncenter\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW8-1024x683.jpg\" alt=\"PW8\" width=\"700\" height=\"467\" /></a>\n\n<span style=\"color: #000000;\">[spacer height=\"20px\"]Throughout our Project Week we encountered with several <strong>organisations</strong> and people in order to discover the multiple sides to the functioning of the Norwegian state and economy.</span>\n<ul>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">The Norwegian parliament, Stortinget</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">A lecture at the University of Oslo on “Women, Gender and Work”</span>\n<ul>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">on how labour is distributed in Norway compared to other European countries</span></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Pro-sentret</span>\n<ul>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">a center that provides help to sex workers in Norway, particularly with safety, emotions and keeping them healthy.</span></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Statoil</span>\n<ul>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">one of the largest oil companies in the world, which also is working a bit with the development of renewable energy in Europe, namely off-shore wind energy. Particularly important is that it is state-owned, but it still functions as a competitive company.</span></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Barne-, ungdoms- og familiedirektoratet</span>\n<ul>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">the Child Protection Agency of Norway, where we learned about when they actually take action, in particular with immigrant children, who might be used to a different upbringing. We also learned how they function within the Norwegian state, collaborating with other organisations to ensure a national protocol.</span></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<blockquote>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">We wanted to investigate the truthfulness of the stereotypes commonly perpetuated in the classroom.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Norway is often internationally recognized as the ‘’optimal’’ society, due to high levels of quality of life, and low levels of corruption and poverty. However, the truth is often more convoluted. Particularly the increase in right-wing ideologies sparked by terrorists attacks on 22nd of July by Anders Behring Breivik, reinforced by the recent refugee crisis. We chose this project because we were very interested in how this economic and political system is achieved and implemented.</span></p>\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW6.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-374\"><img class=\"wp-image-374 size-large aligncenter\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW6-1024x576.jpg\" alt=\"PW6\" width=\"700\" height=\"394\" /></a>\n\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW7.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-373\"><img class=\"wp-image-373 size-large aligncenter\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW7-1024x683.jpg\" alt=\"PW7\" width=\"700\" height=\"467\" /></a>\n\n<span style=\"color: #000000;\">[spacer height=\"20px\"]Our main objective was to learn more of the economic situation in Norway. We wanted to investigate the truthfulness of the stereotypes commonly perpetuated in the classroom. We achieved them by visiting several organisations very much involved in the management of Norway as a state and could provide us insights in the situation currently.</span>\n<h3><span style=\"color: #000000;\">General program and a detailed itinerary of Thursday</span></h3>\n<ul>\n<ul>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Saturday: Frognerparken (Vigeland sculpture park) - Slottet (Palace) - Nationaltheatret (National theatre)</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Sunday: Nasjonalgalleriet (national gallery) - Operaen (Opera)</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Monday: Stortinget (Parliament) - Hjemmefrontmuseet (Resistance museum)</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Tuesday: Hike at Holmenkollen</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Wednesday: Lecture on gender and work, University of Oslo 12.15-14</span>\n<span style=\"color: #000000;\">Munchmuseet (Munch museum)</span>\n<span style=\"color: #000000;\">Exhibition: Mapplethorpe+Munch</span>\n<span style=\"color: #000000;\">Grønland multiethnic immigrants’ zone</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Thursday: Itinerary</span>\n<ul>\n	<li style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">10-12: Pro senteret (prostitution research)</span></li>\n	<li style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Bus 31 to IT Fornebu</span></li>\n	<li style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">13-16.20: Lunch 13-13.30, 13.30-16.00 in room A1031</span></li>\n	<li style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">13.30-14.15: Anca Jalba, Investor relations: Intro: Value chain (exploration, field development, production, refining). The state as owner, Oil fund, transparency, activities worldwide etc.</span></li>\n	<li style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">13.30-14.15: Anca Jalba, Investor relations: Intro: Value chain (exploration, field development, production, refining). The state as owner, Oil fund, transparency, activities worldwide etc.</span></li>\n	<li style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">14.15-15: Fritz H. Eilertsen, Johan Castberg project: Project development in general+examples of major industry projects, Johan Castberg (offshore project development)</span></li>\n	<li style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">15-15.45: Tom James, New energy solutions: Offshore wind etc.</span>\n<span style=\"color: #000000;\"> New energy venture fund, announced on 16 Feb: http://entry.statoil.no/NewsAndMedia/News/2016/Pages/16feb-energy-venture.aspx</span></li>\n	<li style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">16.30: Ferry boat from Fornebu (Sjøflyhavna) to Aker brygge</span></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Friday: Barne-, ungdoms- og familiedirektoratet (Child protection services) - Nobel Peace Prize Museum</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Saturday and Sunday: Hiking around Oslo</span></li>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Our PW was particularly based on investigation, so it was very important in discovering something first hand. It links to the UWC mission of learning first hand of different cultures to eradicate hate and racism through the understanding of another person’s culture. For example, while traveling home on the metro, several people noticed Adithya’s hand bleeding, so they offered tissues and plasters. This gave those who didn’t know much about the people of Norway were positively surprised with this kindness. Some of the values we demonstrated were the values of international and intercultural understanding by departing on this culture week to a culture that most of us were unfamiliar with and compassion and service by handing some of our packed food to people on the street.</span></p>\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW9.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-371\"><img class=\"wp-image-371 size-large aligncenter\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW9-1024x640.png\" alt=\"PW9\" width=\"700\" height=\"438\" /></a>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">[spacer height=\"20px\"]All in all, our project week was a success of investigating the society of Norway and its history. We learned a lot about the developmental status of Norway, particularly also its scopes of international understanding, such as the Nobel Peace Prize committee. We all for sure widened our understanding of Norway and how we look upon other cultures in comparison.</span></p>\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/Pw10.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-370\"><img class=\"wp-image-370 size-large aligncenter\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/Pw10-1024x683.jpg\" alt=\"Pw10\" width=\"700\" height=\"467\" /></a>\n\n&nbsp;', 'Oslo, Norway', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'feb16-oslo-norway', '', '', '2017-06-23 10:07:28', '2017-06-23 10:07:28', '', 0, 'http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/?p=369', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(376, 1, '2016-03-14 09:23:56', '2016-03-14 09:23:56', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><strong>Information about organizations:</strong></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><strong><u>Syrian Education Commission</u></strong>:This is a non-profit, non-political civil society organization that is specialized in the educational process in all its stages. It takes cares of the Syrian students by monitoring and seeking solutions for them through values such as teamwork, originality and modernity, credibility and transparency and professional standards. They have created many projects but the one that we visited was the “Project of Dropout Pupils”, which consists in establishing centers in Turkey for educating and rehabilitating students who have been deprived of education in order to prevent them from wandering in the streets and getting lost in the mazes of ignorance and terrorism.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><u><strong>[spacer height=\"20px\"]ASAM (Istanbul’s unit)</strong>:</u> The Association for Solidarity with Asylum Seekers and Migrants (ASAM) was established in Ankara on December 22, 1995 as a non-profit and non-governmental organization. The primary goal of ASAM is to create solutions to the problems that refugees and asylum seekers encounter in Turkey, to help them to fulfill their primary needs and to support them to provide access for fundamental rights and services. ASAM provides services to refugees and asylum seekers without discrimination on the grounds of language, religion, sex, race, sexual orientation and political ideology.(Veronica, UWCM\'17)</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW12.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-383\"><img class=\"wp-image-383 size-large aligncenter\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW12-1024x683.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px\" srcset=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW12-300x200.jpg 300w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW12-768x512.jpg 768w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW12-1024x683.jpg 1024w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW12-272x182.jpg 272w\" alt=\"PW12\" width=\"700\" height=\"467\"></a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW14.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-381\"><img class=\"wp-image-381 size-large aligncenter\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW14-1024x576.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px\" srcset=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW14-300x169.jpg 300w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW14-768x432.jpg 768w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW14-1024x576.jpg 1024w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW14.jpg 1334w\" alt=\"PW14\" width=\"700\" height=\"394\"></a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><strong>[spacer height=\"20px\"]Why this project week?</strong></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">We chose this project week for couple of reasons. The first one is the activity, which is helping Syrian refugees. As we all know, many Syrians left their country, which is in a situation of a brutal civil war, in order to start their life again. We felt obligated to help them, and especially the kids, who are the next generation. Another reason is the location. Many people assume that Turkey is not a safe place because of what they hear in the media. We wanted to go there in order to see what Turkey is really is, and it turned out to be one of the most welcoming places we have ever been to! Despite the media, Turkey is safe, Istanbul is safe, and it was important to prove that.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">(Achiad, UWCM’16)</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW11.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-384\"><img class=\"wp-image-384 size-large aligncenter\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW11-1024x576.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px\" srcset=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW11-300x169.jpg 300w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW11-768x432.jpg 768w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW11-1024x576.jpg 1024w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW11.jpg 1334w\" alt=\"PW11\" width=\"700\" height=\"394\"></a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><strong>[spacer height=\"20px\"]One of our days: </strong></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Thursday 11th of February -&nbsp;</span><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Day four.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #333333;\">This day was our second day in the organisation “Al Asam”.&nbsp;We left our apartment that is in the area of Sultan Ahmet at approximately 9 o\'clock to go to Karaköy.&nbsp;From that point we had to walk more than one hour. It was really difficult because the city is like a mountain and we do need to climb especially the way we had taken that day.&nbsp;We arrived to the organisation at around 10 and there was a Turkish lesson for the children (3 to 8 years old). We joined the lesson and helped the children with memorizing exercise.&nbsp;After the end of the lesson we had a lot of fun activities with them and this was the most important and enjoying moment of the journey.&nbsp;At 3 o\'clock the second group of students came. They were mainly teenagers and with a highest age of 15. The day before we have gone with them near to the sea for their photography lesson.&nbsp;That day they had hip hop dance and singing lesson. The teachers were really professional and they danced very well. We also joined the dance lesson. And we had fun. The day before during the way to the sea they have taught us some Arabic and we taught them our first languages.&nbsp;At the end of the dance lesson was the singing lesson. Each of the teenagers had their own lyrics that they sing to express what they cannot say through music. We also participated to that lesson by doing random freestyle on a bit.&nbsp;At the end of the day we had an exchanges of addresses with them to keep being in touch.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">(Naimatou, UWCM’17)</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW15.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-380\"><img class=\"wp-image-380 size-large aligncenter\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW15-1024x681.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px\" srcset=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW15-300x200.jpg 300w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW15-768x511.jpg 768w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW15-1024x681.jpg 1024w\" alt=\"PW15\" width=\"700\" height=\"466\"></a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><strong>[spacer height=\"20px\"]Our objectives :</strong></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Our learning goals and objectives are to build project planning skills through the organization of the project week, build communication skills through the contact with Syrian organizations, become more aware of the situation of the Syrian children in foreign countries and have an impact on them through our own effort. During the project week in Istanbul we achieved our learning goals and objectives fully. Meanwhile, we planned the trip in Turkey entirely on our own: we booked the flight tickets, apartments and navigated ourselves to different locations, while everything went on smoothly. Also, we had a very good time with both organizations we worked with. We contacted them beforehand and arrived on time. They were very welcoming and there was no miscommunication within the process. Sitting together with Syrian kids from different age groups in the same room, we had a great opportunity to interact with them closely and understand them better. Although there were huge language barriers among us, as we couldn’t speak arabic nor turkish, they didn’t stop us from being friends with those innocent, cheerful kids. At the end of the day we became from very close to one another and too hard to say goodbye. However, despite the fact that we enjoyed a lot working with the organization, we did identify several problems and difficult that the Syrian refugees encountered. A lot of them are suffering from poverty, because of their family inability to make a living, the kids themselves have to work by selling tissues to pedestrians. Though the organizations provide basic education for them, they don’t have money for textbooks and the basic educational resources. For them education is a luxury. We felt very sad about that and through the speech we gave them, and all the games we played with them, we hoped that they would never give up their hope and dreams and thrive with the help of education.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">(Nina, UWCM’17)</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW17.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-378\"><img class=\"wp-image-378 size-large aligncenter\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW17-1024x681.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px\" srcset=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW17-300x200.jpg 300w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW17-768x511.jpg 768w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW17-1024x681.jpg 1024w\" alt=\"PW17\" width=\"700\" height=\"466\"></a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW18.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-377\"><img class=\"wp-image-377 size-large aligncenter\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW18-1024x681.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px\" srcset=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW18-300x200.jpg 300w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW18-768x511.jpg 768w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW18-1024x681.jpg 1024w\" alt=\"PW18\" width=\"700\" height=\"466\"></a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><strong>[spacer height=\"20px\"]The importance of this Project Week :<em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </em></strong></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">We headed to Turkey to help with the syrian refugees. The trip there was a challenge, because a lot of us come from priviledged backgrounds. We learned that the world is far from ideal and that there is a long way to go. However we all believed that if we fight and if we taught the children to fight as well for everyone’s rights, the world will become a better place. Staying with the children was a personal challenge because of the language barrier, which was interesting because as much as we were different we were still able to comprehend each other and to build a special relationship. Also, dealing with children and seeing them facing a such situation where they flee from their home and have to find a way to survive in the street made us sad, angry and more compassionate towards the cause. But we were there, we showed them support and even if they were young and might not have ununderstood why we left so early, at least we made them smile and this wasn’t the kind of smiles you can see in Western Europe. These were pure smiles that you cannot immitate. As bad as their situation can be, you can still see the way they are interested by anything and the happiness they can share with you. I think this project week was definitely important for each of us in the sense that we directly saw what we used to hear on the TV, medias, internet and that it changed somehow our mind. We all come from different countries and for some of us, going in Turkey with such a different culture than where we are from was eye opening to the similarities and differences that western and eastern cultures can have. The fact that one paraguayan, one guatemalan, two french, one moroccan, one egyptian, one burkinabe, one israeli and one chinese show that it is possible to help and that it is not that complicated to help people different from us.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">(Mathilde, UWCM’17)</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW16.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-379\"><img class=\"wp-image-379 size-large aligncenter\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW16-1024x681.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px\" srcset=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW16-300x200.jpg 300w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW16-768x511.jpg 768w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW16-1024x681.jpg 1024w\" alt=\"PW16\" width=\"700\" height=\"466\"></a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">This project week lasted four days, but our actions won’t stop there. We come from all over the world and with this experience we can continue, at even bigger scales, to help</span>.&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #000000;\">The refugee crisis is not a joke and media don’t share everything, so it’s our own responsibility to decide whether or not we should try to save people who die or children who are losing their childhood</span>.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW13.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-382\"><img class=\"wp-image-382 size-large\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW13-1024x683.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px\" srcset=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW13-300x200.jpg 300w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW13-768x512.jpg 768w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW13-1024x683.jpg 1024w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW13-272x182.jpg 272w\" alt=\"PW13\" width=\"700\" height=\"467\"></a></p>', 'Istanbul, Turkey', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'feb16-istanbul-turkey', '', '', '2017-06-23 09:51:00', '2017-06-23 09:51:00', '', 0, 'http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/?p=376', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(410, 1, '2016-03-15 07:56:27', '2016-03-15 07:56:27', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">by Ulises, Oumaima, Ceri, Charlotte, Valeria, Martin, Pietro, Sofia, Aya and Kathleen</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">[spacer height=\"20px\"]We just arrived at Weez airport in Dusseldorf it is only 4:20 and we have to wait until 9 in order to take our flight to Fez, Morocco. An atmosphere of excitement covers our team since we left campus. Another country, another continent, another culture is just three hours and a half from us.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">[spacer height=\"20px\"]We just arrived in <strong>Fez</strong>, Morocco. The weather was surprisingly fresh, with a lot of dry wind. The effects of globalization could be seen since the moment we landed because the airport was just renovated and the installations where incredibly well designed. Furthermore, as we move along the city with the help of Aya’s parents, the effect of globalization could be seen more and more. Houses, large buildings were replacing the olive plantations in the surroundings of Fez.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/Capture-4.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-411\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-411 size-full\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/Capture-4.png\" alt=\"Capture\" width=\"605\" height=\"452\" /></a></p>\n\n<h2 style=\"text-align: justify;\">[spacer height=\"20px\"]Our first Moroccan breakfast!</h2>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Sadly not all of us eat meat! However the ones we do, it was amazing! Eggs with a different kind of meat, “man” (no idea how it is spelled but it was heavenly delicious), some other sweet pieces of bread that were just full of taste. The environment around the restaurant was busier than our usual Maastricht but with a calm environment. A ride of at least three hours was ahead of us, we went through Rabat without stopping just to barely see it. <strong>Casablanca</strong> was our main goal by this day, however in our way we encountered with beautiful deserted landscapes that for many of us were totally new. Morocco is incredibly huge! So much free land.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">We discover the preference of Oumaima towards Indians! But we are going to keep the lucky one anonymously!</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">[spacer height=\"20px\"]As soon as we arrived at Aya’s house in Casablanca, the dinner was waiting for us! Well, we thought it was the dinner but it was the gate that is before the dinner. And the dinner was a combination of different salads, olives, chicken, beef which was perfectly combined. We all sleep really well that night! The first Breakfast! Pancakes, tangerines, bread, milk, amlo and more! Was just wonderful! Afterwards, we went to the French school, however, our entrance was not permitted because they were afraid of terrorist attacks. (If like a Mexican a Salvadoran, or even a girl from Hong Kong will attack) However, we observed how the impact of the globalization affected the areas surrounding the French school.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">[spacer height=\"20px\"]We visited the Mosque Hassan II, one of the biggest in the whole world. We had the chance to visit inside of it. The amount of money that the king had to put on it has to be incredibly huge! Also, we had the chance to visit the biggest mall in the whole continent of Africa. An aquarium was waiting for us just in the middle of the mall.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">[spacer height=\"20px\"]Hammam! The boys and the hammam got along pretty well! Hammam was a kind of spa where you get scrubbed in a warm room. The guys slept really well! After we all ate real couscous!</p>\n\n<h2 style=\"text-align: justify;\">[spacer height=\"20px\"]On our way to Marrakech!</h2>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">We just took the train to <b>Marrakesh</b>! The train was surprisingly well maintained. The impact of globalization had reached almost everywhere but not everyone. The development of the city of Marrakesh is incredibly high, however not everybody has the access to all of this new resources. In Marrakesh, we had the chance to discuss this and another type of problems with other teenagers. We had the chance to discuss the state of the monarchy is nowadays and how this and external factors affect the society as a whole. A lack of opportunities and a sense of censorship surrounds the youth we talked to, problems that are common everywhere else but that its roots are well into the ground, in such a way that is hard to find a solution.</p>\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/Capture-5.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-412\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-412 size-full\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/Capture-5.png\" alt=\"Capture\" width=\"420\" height=\"558\" /></a>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Marrakesh we had the chance to visit characteristic market which makes this city famous worldwide. A number of colors and different artifacts is characteristic of this place. Scarfs, food, seafood, spices anything you want can be found there. Morocco ends up being a country where all our expectations were and were not right at the same time. We experimented hospitality to the fullest from Aya’s parents, we felt morocco as a living organism made up of great people which are always moving, working, dancing, cooking, singing, playing all the time. Morocco ends up being for most of us the trigger for a paradigm shift towards our stereotypes. Morocco for project week, was a wise decision, not only for the particular environment but also for the people and the conversations we had with them. It is different to read about a country’s situation than experiencing it. We left Morocco with a feeling of hearts and flowers, with the aim to go back and actually immerse ourselves within their culture.</p>', 'Morocco', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'feb16-morocco', '', '', '2017-06-23 10:07:17', '2017-06-23 10:07:17', '', 0, 'http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/?p=410', 0, 'post', '', 0),
