(486, 1, '2016-03-17 07:54:14', '2016-03-17 07:54:14', 'For our project week we endeavored to the great lands of Scandinavia to face the cold winds and grey skies. Actually it wasn\'t that cold and we were graced with a few days of sun. We worked with an organization in Sweden called Mosaik a branch of a larger organisation called Students for Christ Europe (SFC Europe). This is in an organization leading to broaden discussions about faith, our beliefs and why we believe. One of our goals was to reach out to students in Malmo on their views of faith particularly Christianity and get their opinions on what role religion has in Sweden. In addition, though Sweden can be identified as a prosperous country the region we went to still faces some degree of poverty. This is especially faced by the Romani people. So with the church we volunteered at a homeless shelter where we helped to prepare meals and take care of other necessities such as making the beds and cleaning up. The people staying there usually pay a small fee of less than 2 euros which includes a night stay, 3 meals and other utilities. The church aims to help as many homeless people but does this with a fee as to give the people a sense of responsibility, dignity and a reward for their hard work.\n\nDuring our project week we decided to try and achieve the following goals:\n<ol>\n	<li>Organize activities outside the campus.\nThe activities that we took part in were not completely organized by us alone, as most of the work we did was in collaboration with other organizations. However we took initiative and made clear as to what and how we would be doing. For example when we volunteered at the homeless shelter. The work itself was not organized by us but we made contact and were willing to take part.</li>\n	<li>Explore a new country and culture.\nAfter we had completed our service and during our breaks we were able to converse with the local people whom we were working with. This allowed us to get an understanding of the culture from a primary source. Also, on our final night, we were hosted by a resident family. During our time there we learned much about the culture and history of that area. Not only did we chat with locals but we also made time for exploring the city and experience the area. We spent many hours walking the city and familiarizing ourselves with our environment</li>\n	<li>Design and pursue a student-led project.\nThe trip and project were organized by ourselves in collaboration with the organization that we were assisting. Also, we lead ourselves during the project. At times working with the organization and at time our own work.</li>\n	<li>Improve your organization, communication and collaboration skills.\nOur trip was great organization experience as it allowed us to work without relying on an adult. Also our communication and collaboration between the group and with third parties improved. We were able to work together as a group without any mishaps or conflict.</li>\n	<li>Get to know more about yourself and your group.\nTogether as a group we had an amazing time and learned much about each other. This was done late at night chatting but also during our service times and during planning. Even interacting with the third party people taught us something about how we interacted with people away from home and the UWC.</li>\n	<li>Share and spread the UWC mission and values.\nWhile doing our service we were often asked as to why we came and why we were helping. Dutifully we told them about the UWC and its mission. People responded positively to this and we’re excited that such a mission exists. People were also impressed that such student led initiatives existed.</li>\n	<li>Achieve a positive (social) change.\nThe work we did helping at the homeless shelter created a more positive environment not only through helping with the labor, but also through encouragement and motivation.</li>\n</ol>\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/Capture-6.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-488\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-488 size-full\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/Capture-6.png\" alt=\"Capture\" width=\"684\" height=\"381\" /></a>\n\n[spacer height=\"20px\"]We decided to join the project for a number of reasons. Firstly all of us were very interested in volunteering at the homeless shelter and interested to serve in any way that we could as at first it was shock that this issue existed in a scandinavian country. In addition this was a unique project, that none of us had never done. We were all extremely anxious to talk about our own beliefs and opinions to strangers but wanted to challenge ourselves, especially by going to another country.\n\n[spacer height=\"20px\"]Even after all this said one might still ask: ‘Still what made your PW so important? How did your PW even link to the UWC mission and values? Was it any use to go, really?’\n\n[spacer height=\"20px\"]In congruence with all the numerous, so-true points mentioned above, during our project week we also learned more about our Christian faith. This was really important to us for as students in the UWC community we would like to contribute to the diversity in faith by knowing more about our actual spiritual beliefs, so that we are able to share those ideas. In the UWC mission it states that we must strive to reach ‘the celebration of difference’, and by going on this project week we added more difference to be celebrated in our mainly secular school.\n\n[spacer height=\"20px\"]On our project week we did not only further establish Jesus’ love for us, what we also did was serve at a homeless shelter. The security guard on the first day told us to speak of the shelter to the public in discretion in order to avoid complaints from locals about how homeless people get everything for free from the government. This not only incorrect opinion in the case of the homeless shelter we worked at since they do pay a fee of 15 krona for a bed, a grooming packet, dinner and breakfast, is unfortunately the mentality some have towards those with no money. We didn’t even know that it wasn’t for free either but through this experience we got more informed and therefore less biased, which is also what UWC aims to instill in us.\n\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/Capture-7.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-489\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-489 size-full\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/Capture-7.png\" alt=\"Capture\" width=\"649\" height=\"833\" /></a>\n\n[spacer height=\"20px\"]As a team we looked out for each other even if it just meant encouraging words on our long walks, making sure everybody woke up on time or attempting to relieving another’s blister pain through well- meant footwear advice. The project week was all great way to emulate the ‘mutual responsibility and respect’ part of the UWC mission statement. Furthermore, when making food for the homeless we had to be very hygienic and respectful by wearing gloves and washing our hands. It is often very easy to bend the rules and not care because no one would know so you wouldn\'t get caught but we practiced our integrity well and out of respect for the shelter seekers, we handled their food appropriately.\n\n[spacer height=\"20px\"]From the project week our friendships grew stronger, we got a taster of what being a responsible young adult is like in the ‘real world’ away from the protection of our safe, idealistically minded UWC community.\n\n[spacer height=\"20px\"]All this seems pretty worthwhile to us.', 'Sweden', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'feb16-sweden', '', '', '2017-06-23 10:07:09', '2017-06-23 10:07:09', '', 0, 'http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/?p=485', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(495, 1, '2016-03-20 22:35:15', '2016-03-20 22:35:15', 'On 21st October Michal Steyn, chairman and one of the founders of <a href=\"http://stcmaastricht.nl/en/\">ServetheCity Maastricht</a> (STC), visited us during our YSE session to help us understand our host city better and make us think about our attitudes and actions towards our new community.\n\nThis software engineer from South Africa had earlier in his professional life joined a group of friends with their startup technology company iKubu, which eventually invested a micro radar system and was later acquired by an American company.\n\nMichal moved to the USA in 2014, where he started his current software consultancy business. In 2015 he relocated with his family to Maastricht, where he divides his time between engineering and STC.\n\nThese are some of Michal\'s inspiring lines:\n\n<em>\"What if we got to know the members of our community by name and not by numbers and needs?</em>\n\n<em>Each community has something to give and something to receive. Don\'t pity them, have compassion!</em>\n\n<em>There are needs even in this room, walk around with new eyes, be aware of the problems around you.</em>\n\n<em>Starting a business must be one of the most humanitarian actions you can do: feeding a family is entrepreneurship.</em>\n\n<em>Keep in mind always the triple bottom line: social equity, economic, and environmental factors =&gt; PEOPLE, PLANET &amp; PROFIT.</em>\n\n<em>Be playful and dream again, don´t let education ruin your creativity.\"</em>\n\nMichal also talked about their current projects with the Refugee Centre in Maastricht.', 'Serve The City Maastricht - Michal Steyn', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'serve-the-city-maastricht-michal-steyn__trashed', '', '', '2017-06-23 08:59:46', '2017-06-23 08:59:46', '', 0, 'http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/?p=495', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(497, 1, '2016-03-20 22:51:09', '2016-03-20 22:51:09', 'On 4th November, Vincent Frenken visited us to present a map of Maastricht and neighbouring communities in terms of social challenges faced especially by youth.\n\nVincent has worked for many years for Trayekt, the equivalent of the Social Services in NL, and he works mostly at night with youth in the streets: \"lover boys\", female prostitution, etc.\n\nThis was a shocking presentation for many of us since we were not aware of the dimension of these problems.\n\nThere\'s also a street culture by which some youth make up big stories of what they have done that aren´t always true.\n\nBesides these issues, one of the biggest problems among youngsters and young families or single-headed-households in Maastricht is the level of indebtedness, which at times makes these people resort to illegal and/or criminal activities to make quick money.\n\n&nbsp;', 'Trayekt - Vincent Frenken', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'trayekt-vincent-frenken__trashed', '', '', '2017-06-23 08:59:20', '2017-06-23 08:59:20', '', 0, 'http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/?p=497', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(499, 1, '2016-03-20 23:20:51', '2016-03-20 23:20:51', 'On 20 November ten of our DP1 students taking part in the YSE Programme attended in Brussels a one day event organised by <a href=\"http://belgium.ashoka.org/splash\">Ashoka Belgium</a>, in collaboration with their <a href=\"http://belgium.ashoka.org/nl/changemaker-scholen\">8 Ashoka Changemaker Schools</a> and <a href=\"http://www.mobileschool.org/nl\">Mobile School/Streetwize</a>. The BELGIAN BLAST brought teachers, other frontline educators and students together to boost the movement for innovation and change in education.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\nA summary of the event here: <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8Eh0rljK5fk\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8Eh0rljK5fk</a>', 'Belgian Blast - Ashoka Belgium', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'belgian-blast-ashoka-belgium__trashed', '', '', '2017-06-23 09:49:31', '2017-06-23 09:49:31', '', 0, 'http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/?p=499', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(502, 1, '2016-03-21 00:05:05', '2016-03-21 00:05:05', 'On Monday 23rd November, Bert Jongen - a senior member of the local government, long-life advocate for the rights of people with disabilities and an expert in Social Entrepreneurship in the Limburg region - joined DP2 students for a chat within the UWCM YSE Hub.\n\nBert is the author of ‘<em>Werken met Passie. </em><em>SociaalOndernemen in the Praktijk</em>and’, a book about those entrepreneurs working with passion in the Netherlands and the main social enterprises in this country.\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/IMG_0639.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-503\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-503\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/IMG_0639-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"IMG_0639\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\nStudents refreshed their ideas about the key features of a social enterprise and learnt about social enterprises in the Limburg region.\n\n<em>\"A social enterprise must fulfill the 3Ps: People, Planet and Profit. Profit is not their goal but a tool to enable their social project, to make it sustainable. The money is used to cover the costs of the project.\"</em>\n\n\"A social enterprise is a way to work within the capitalist system to find solutions to problems. [...] It\'s about the intention behind the \'helping\'...people and disabilities or other\".\n\nThere\'s now specific law in NL and a certification for social enterprises.\n\nThere are 25 firms in NL specialised in employment opportunities for people with disabilities as there are only 1 in 4 chances of finding a job as a person with disability in NL.\n\nCrowdfunding donors are a good idea to start financing your project, at least to cover costs.\n\nThe examples of Ben&amp;Jerry ice-cream and StreetwiZe were discussed by the group.\n\nBert highlighted the following as the main social problems in Maastricht at the moment:\n<ul>\n	<li>Unemployment</li>\n	<li>Solitude of elderly people (above 50 yeas old)</li>\n	<li>Youth with severe debt (several thousand euros)</li>\n</ul>\nThere are no social enterprises at the municipal level but the local goverment sponsors 140 social organisations. For example, Trajekt receives 12 million euros per year to run projects.\n\nBert mentioned the big niche for UWC Maastricht students starting social entrepreneurial projects and pointed at the potential of a project to awaken the province about funds to help young people start social enterprises.\n\n&nbsp;', 'Bert Jongen: \"Working with Passion\"', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'bert-jongen-working-with-passion__trashed', '', '', '2017-06-23 09:00:00', '2017-06-23 09:00:00', '', 0, 'http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/?p=502', 0, 'post', '', 0),
