(507, 1, '2016-03-21 00:12:33', '2016-03-21 00:12:33', '<u>Integrated activities and projects with local industry 2015-2016</u>\nThis is a programme initiated by the Province of Limburg with the goal of making connections between the provincial government, educational institutions in the province and the local industry. Students from UWC Maastricht joined two regional vocational schools to work on two case studies developed by two local companies.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nUWC Maastricht students were matched with the following two companies:\n\n1.Smurfit Kappa (Roermond)\nSmurfit Kappa is one of the world leading providers of paper-based packaging (44.000 employees worldwide). Together with the Cita Verde College in Roermond and Leeuwenborgh in Sittard, our students worked on a project where they depicted the actual working of circular economy for Smurfit Kappa. Students were asked to think of a purpose for some of the waste materials from Smurfit Kappa. How can they be developed into a product? Our students followed the process of research, lab work and design and presented that as part of their broader case study of how circular economy works in practice. They developed a sort of marketing of Smurfit Kappa’s sustainability management and <u>won the competition</u>.\n\n2. Arion (Geleen)\nA company producing innovative solutions for the healthcare market. Examples of their products are aids to pull on and off compression stockings and products that allow washing patients without water. Especially the last product group, the washing without water products, is growing enormously in the last couple of years. They therefore developed a research question for students to focus on.\n<em>“How can Arion make use of cultural, anthropological, philosophical, and historical findings on washing in general in the countries where it is currently active (NL, BE, DE, DK, ES) and is going to be active (UK, FR, SE)?”</em>\nThe goals of the activity were:\n\n- To provide students with an insight into the daily running of a business.\n\n- To allow students to independently work on a real life case study.\n-  For students to explore how innovation can be a force of positive change.\n- To create a network between our school, other schools, businesses and the local\n\ngovernment.\nUWC Maastricht will continue its participation in the project next academic year.\n\n<strong><em> </em></strong>\n\n<strong><em> </em></strong>', 'Limburg & Co. Project', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'limburg-co-project__trashed', '', '', '2017-06-23 08:59:38', '2017-06-23 08:59:38', '', 0, 'http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/?p=507', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(509, 1, '2016-03-21 00:17:15', '2016-03-21 00:17:15', 'On 3rd February 2016 our YSE students (almost 150) visited five social enterprises in Eindhoven, Utrecht and Amsterdam. This was an Offsite Education opportunity within the Youth Social Entrepreneurship Programme.\n\nStudents and YSE facilitators visited <a href=\"http://www2.thecolourkitchen.com/en\">The Colour Kitchen</a> in Eindhoven, <a href=\"http://www.healthyentrepreneurs.nl/\">Healthy Entrepreneurs</a> in Utrecht and the <a href=\"http://www.proportionfoundation.org/\">ProPortion</a> Foundation, <a href=\"http://www.nudge-global-leadership-challenge.com/nudge/\">Nudge</a> and <a href=\"http://www.social-enterprise.nl/\">Social Enterprise NL</a> in Amsterdam.\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/Group-Healthy-Entrepreneurs.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-510\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-510\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/Group-Healthy-Entrepreneurs-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"Group Healthy Entrepreneurs\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a> <a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/ColourKitchen.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-511\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-511\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/ColourKitchen-300x149.jpg\" alt=\"ColourKitchen\" width=\"300\" height=\"149\" /></a></p>\nRe-known social entrepreneurs such as Jan van Betten (Nudge), Maarten Neve (co-founder of Healthy Entrepreneurs) or Merel Rumping (this young social entrepreneur had pitched for Bill Gates the week before presenting her project <a href=\"http://www.proportionfoundation.org/legbank/\">LegBank</a>, with Pro-Portion Foundation) welcomed UWC Maastricht students and proposed to them different challenges such as designing health products for under 1€ or creating a social media campaign.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nOver all, it was a very inspiring day for our students who also learnt more technical aspects such as the business model behind these enterprises that create a positive social impact, the challenges they face or the strategic importance of creating the right team for their projects.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;', 'Visits to Social Enterprises in NL', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'visits-to-social-enterprises-in-nl__trashed', '', '', '2017-06-23 09:49:24', '2017-06-23 09:49:24', '', 0, 'http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/?p=509', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(523, 1, '2016-06-03 17:46:47', '2016-06-03 17:46:47', 'The project week ‘In Search of Impressionist Eyes’ was aimed to researching French impressionists in the 19th and 20th century in Paris. The Project had a particular focus on Claude Monet, who is often considered to be the father of impressionism. The reason for this project was to investigate how this group of people managed to change the art culture so drastically, and what difficulties they encountered along the way.\n\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/paris.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-524\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-524 size-full\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/paris.jpg\" alt=\"paris\" width=\"1000\" height=\"667\" /></a>\n\nTo start my project and introduce myself to Claude Monet, I went straight to the Marmottan museum. This museum has a permanent exposition dedicated to Monet and contains some of his artworks from various points in his life. This first experience was key to gathering my first impressions of the impressionist movement and Monet’s life, later on I frequently went back to add to the things I noticed on this first visit.\nAfter the first introduction, I moved on to the D’Orsay museum. This second visit included many other impressionist artists of Monet’s time period who lived in France. Also, I was able to see some paintings from impressionists from other countries like Van Gogh, and was able to compare his artworks with the ones I had previously seen. It would be a great extension to this project week to research Van Gogh and Dutch impressionists to see the full impact that the French impressionists had and the differences between the two movements.\n\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/paris7.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-530\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-530 size-full\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/paris7.jpg\" alt=\"paris7\" width=\"640\" height=\"480\" /></a>\n\nOn the second day I visited the Louvre museum, with the objective of seeing the impressionist exhibition of artists in the late 19<sup>th</sup> century, and early 20<sup>th</sup> century. Unfortunately that particular exhibition was closed, along with a few others due to working strike. Even though this obstacle came along, I visited the museum to see the kinds of artistic movements that were present in the past and to get an idea of where exactly impressionism was shifting from\n\nAfter the visit at the Louvre museum, I visited the Orangerie. A museum dedicated and built around Monet’s giant water lilies oil on canvases. The sight of these enormous paintings was breath taking for me, and it was possible for me to understand the severeness of Monet’s sight condition that had manifested towards the end of his life. Monet had to rely on creating enormous paintings since he could no longer see clearly up close.\n\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/paris2.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-525\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-525 size-full\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/paris2.jpg\" alt=\"paris2\" width=\"640\" height=\"480\" /></a>\n\n&nbsp;\n\nAfter seeing an overview of Monet’s painting life and the one of his painter friends, I went to visit the Renoir Gardens in the area of Mon Matre. This area of Paris was and still is known to be a common place where artists lived and met up. During the time I visited, the artists in the area were exposing their artworks in the streets. Experiencing the atmosphere in which Impressionist artists grew and lived was very enriching and mind opening; I had to note that it is important to be surrounded by a community that supports you and in which you feel comfortable to do what you believe in.\n\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/paris3.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-526\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-526 size-full\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/paris3.jpg\" alt=\"paris3\" width=\"640\" height=\"480\" /></a>\n\nThe very last day, to get the final glimpses at Monet’s life, I visited his house in Giverny, where he spent the last years of his life, and created his famous water lily oil on canvases. During these last years Monet’s eyesight worsened with the years, but every time he was able to find ways to improve it he would paint as much as he could to use the full potential of his temporary cure. Visiting his house gave me an insight into what kind of person he was, one that would not simply stop doing what he loved because of old age or other restrictions, he was also known to sit through the coldest and the hottest of days to paint his heart out on canvas before the moment he was trying to capture would disappear. I think the last visit to his house and gardens were a perfect closing to the project week, that left me reflecting on the visit long after it was over.\n\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/paris5.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-528\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-528 size-full\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/paris5.jpg\" alt=\"paris5\" width=\"1000\" height=\"688\" /></a> <a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/paris6.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-529\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-529 size-full\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/paris6.jpg\" alt=\"paris6\" width=\"1000\" height=\"667\" /></a>', 'In Search of Impressionist Eyes - Paris', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'in-search-of-impressionist-eyes-paris-april-27', '', '', '2017-06-23 10:06:50', '2017-06-23 10:06:50', '', 0, 'http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/?p=523', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(533, 1, '2016-06-03 21:46:28', '2016-06-03 21:46:28', '<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For my project week I had worked at Aalborgs Fosvars og Garnisons musuem, which is a museum about world war 2 in Denmark, where mostly volunteers worked. I had worked there for 4 days throughout the May break from 10:00am to 15:00pm each day. At first it was a new experience because I had never worked in Denmark before and to be honest was a bit nervous due to my lack of having spoken Danish in a long time. However it all went well once I got used to things. On the first day it was a bit awkward as they did not exactly have everything thought through and did not know what they wanted me to do. So on the first day I was set to clean and wash the cabinets and display cases that were there. This was not as boring as it actually sounds because I was able to listen to music and explore the events that had occurred throughout Denmark during World War 2. So it was also an educational project week for me. The second and third day I was set to vacuum the area and also clean again, once again getting a detailed look at things I could do. However on the third day I was able to get a free tour of the exhibits and learnt quite a lot. I was able to gain a better understanding of what they actually do and have there and made me glad to see that I am helping out. I was also able to spread a lot of information about UWC since they all were surprised as to me living in Holland and why I was doing service there. The people who were there were very generous. They said that I could take as many breaks as I wanted to and for lunch I could take a soda. They were also very interesting and had worked there for most of their life. On the fourth day I was putting price tags on the goods that they were selling which varied but also had the chance to fix some of the flash lights their which were broken. This was actually a really fun experience because I’ve always had a passion for being able to fix something which is supposed to be broken. I had fixed most of the flashlights although some were beyond fixing. When discussing the project week as a whole I think that it was a very fun experience and would advise other people to do it since it is simple, educational and a fun experience. However I would advise people to do it in a group as it can tend to get quite a bit lonely when doing it by yourself. If you are fond of history I would advise it. I really enjoyed myself and met new people, learnt new cleaning skills and speaking skills as well and social behavior as a whole. This project week was a generally good experience for me and the people I helped. </span>\n\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/Denmark.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-534\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-534 size-full\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/Denmark.png\" alt=\"Denmark\" width=\"555\" height=\"372\" /></a> <a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/denmark2.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-535\"><img class=\"wp-image-535 size-full aligncenter\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/denmark2.png\" alt=\"denmark2\" width=\"662\" height=\"439\" /></a>', 'Denmark WWII Museum', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'denmark-daniel', '', '', '2017-06-23 10:06:43', '2017-06-23 10:06:43', '', 0, 'http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/?p=533', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(537, 1, '2016-06-03 22:03:30', '2016-06-03 22:03:30', '<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">We are a group of 6 girls: Chiara from Italy; Emi from Malaysia; Hana from Japan; Hellen from Eritrea and Sudan; Jana from Germany and Len from Myanmar. Our project was to investigate the social impact of the Berlin Wall. Throughout our project week we went to museums, got to know the city and had meaningful interviews with people on this issue. Due to the different backgrounds we are from, each one of us had different perspectives. We would sit and share our feelings each day, and it gave us the opportunity to reach a more complete understanding of our research.</span>\n\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/berlin2.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-539\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-539 size-full\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/berlin2.png\" alt=\"berlin2\" width=\"664\" height=\"441\" /></a>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Day 1 : On the first day, we went to the Deutsches Historisches museum, where we learnt about Germany before and after the World Wars. The next museum is the DDR museum. We observed the impact of the Wall, the ruling parties, personal stories, and ideologies from both East and West Germany at that time by using both primary and secondary resources available there.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Day 2:  At the Deutsches Technik, we saw a wide variety of technologies that brought Germany to its current shape such as weaving machines, boats, planes and cars.  In the computer section, we learned that computer skills were developing in the US during the separation of Berlin, so we could imagine the more developed life in the West side than the East.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Jewish museum showed us the history of their people, culture and religion starting from when Jewish religion started.  However, it wasn’t only about the beautiful culture.  We also saw the friction between Germans due to the differences in their religion.  The unique atmosphere of the museum\'s architecture stimulated our imagination.  </span>\n\n<strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Day 3: We visited the East Side Gallery and the German Resistance Memorial. The East Side Gallery is a kilometer of the Berlin Wall where art pieces have been drawn. There were creative drawings depicting the political and social issues. We saw how the Berlin Wall looked like and how the two sides were separated. Then, we went to the German Resistance Memorial. This was a memorial about the Berlin Wall and included stories of the people that lived at that time and their attempts of crossing the wall. Some succeeded and others were killed while trying to cross the wall. Around 138 people were killed trying to cross from the East to the West. They crossed because life was easier and there was more freedom in the west than in the East.</span></strong>\n\nDay 4: We conducted interviews with some locals and tourists on their knowledge and views about the Wall. We decided to go to the Tiergarten Park and approach people to ask questions. Some of the questions were:\n<ul>\n	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">What are your views on the Berlin Wall?</span></li>\n	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Were you taught anything about the Berlin Wall when you were still in school? If so, what information were you given?</span></li>\n	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Do you see any difference between the East and West Berlin today?</span></li>\n	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Do you still feel the effects of the Wall today?</span></li>\n	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Some people still feel that the Wall should be present today, what do you think</span></li>\n</ul>\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">We have interviewed around 15 people in the park, and found some very interesting views and perspective. We asked whether they feel that the wall should still exist, we got very different answers where some people were against it, while some people felt that the wall could also be beneficial in terms of jobs, standard of living etc, as the people are taken care by the government.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Through this project, we were able to learn about the history of the Wall and the separation of Berlin. We learned greatly about the impact this had on society. With two very different government systems in East and West, people were treated very differently. People were separated from each other for 28 years. A whole generation of people developing very different political ideologies, beliefs and attitudes, as all east-west relations had been forcibly terminated. The consequences of this political and social division have left their marks on society to this day.  It was very interesting to see and hear first-hand the impact this had on the Berlin society through conducting interviews with people on different ages and visiting memorial sites and museums, which enabled us to experience the issue in a much more authentic way.</span>\n\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/berlin.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-538\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-538 size-full\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/berlin.png\" alt=\"berlin\" width=\"662\" height=\"374\" /></a>', 'Berlin Wall', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'berlin-wall', '', '', '2017-06-23 10:06:22', '2017-06-23 10:06:22', '', 0, 'http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/?p=537', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(542, 1, '2016-06-03 22:21:21', '2016-06-03 22:21:21', '<b>What did we do?</b>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For our project week, we decided to explore the country that suffered massacres and war crimes not longer than one and a half decades ago. Not only did the numerous colonizations and invasions in history have an impact on the country’s later developments, but up to this day it is still not internationally recognised as an independent country where the inhabitants still have to bear the ongoing conflicts between itself and its bordering countries. Our team was: Diona (Kosovo), Alon (Israel), JV (Philippines), Victoria (Bolivia), and Lorenzo (French/Italian). We all decided to choose Kosovo as the destination, precisely because of this historical background, which fascinated us. It was a really long trip to get there, we left early on April 28th and arrived to Pristina (Kosovo’s capital) by dawn next morning.  We volunteered with an NGO called “The Ideas Partnership” is a quite new organization founded by young kosovars, and what they do is that they gather volunteers to tackle education, promoting the preservation of cultural heritage and facing environmental challenges in Kosovo and the region, without political or religious affiliation.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">On the first day, we went Janjeva, a small town hiding in hills somewhere in the centre of Kosovo. Janjeva is a place whose unusually diverse cultural history can still be heard in the different languages spoken in its winding dusty streets, and in the wood, plaster and stone of the buildings. There, along with other volunteers, we prepared creativity classes for 2 different groups of children, guiding them through their drawings. It was a bit difficult to communicate with them, as only Diona spoke the language, but nevertheless, their warm spirit allowed is in the end, to make this sharing a memorable experience. We did this 2 other times, as well as English lessons.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Ideas Partnership doesn’t work on Sundays nor Labor Day, as the children attend to this extra learning opportunities right after their normal school hours, so in these two days we went a bit farther, and took a day off to Diona’s hometown Gjakova, were we walked around, met friends and family, and visited a post-war memorial of the victims. Once we got back to action, we went to Fushë Kosova, which is another section of the NGO’s program. Fushë Kosova is perhaps five miles away from the centre of Pristina. Families there are trying to live in single rooms on 60 hours a month, each and one of them with different and sadder stories; children who don’t go to school because they lack shoes and proper clothes, children who have limited access to basic education, etc. The employment of the majority is going through bins for scrap metal to sell for a few cents, and children begging in the streets. There we took lead of the English classes and the reading program. We were separated in different groups which were divided by age and proficiency in English, but these activities were only present in of the days. During the last day we took part of the creativity day, where we shared facts and legends of our own cultures, and learned about theirs. This last one, was very successful and one could see the joy around everybody, specially when they had to guess our countries and got it right (only once). Fushë Kosova also supports the Changemakers, which is a group of community members who want to improve their community themselves by organizing clean-up campaigns, and even took initiative in the creation of a kindergarten. The Changemakers group was specifically interesting to see, as a until-now-successful social entrepreneurship project.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Once our service days came to an end, we took those last 2 days to travel a bit more. We went to Prizren, an astonishingly beautiful old city, with a huge influence from the Ottoman Empire. We visited the fortress, hiked a bit, ate delicious traditional dishes. All team members agreed that our stay in Prizren was very relaxing, and brought us more together as a group. On the last day, we went to Gjakova again, and did some for walking. That same night, we took a taxi to Skopje  (Macedonia), catched our plane to Charleroi and returned to campus. It was a really nice experience that all of us will remember for a long time.</span>\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">PW Quote: “omg! This is so cheap!”</span>\n\n[gallery size=\"large\" ids=\"543,544,547,548,549,550,551,546,545\"]', 'Project Week in Kosovo', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'may-2016-project-week-in-kosovo', '', '', '2017-06-23 10:06:13', '2017-06-23 10:06:13', '', 0, 'http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/?p=542', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(553, 1, '2016-06-03 22:32:16', '2016-06-03 22:32:16', 'This past May break, the WinBin project week team set about on their project of bringing about positive environmental change, one bin at a time. Colin, Daan, Martijn, Tom, Cato, Elias and I (Ofek) were all motivated and excited to start this short week of building and creating recycling bins to be placed around the school. The idea behind WinBin was for us to plan and initiate our own project week of making bins after we realized there was a distinct lack of places within school where recyclable trash could be thrown away. We were all aware of the global importance of recycling, and were determined to do our bit on the fight against global warming. After recognizing this issue within the school community, we set about to try and change it by implementing Colin’s “green bin” idea from last year all around the school. Colin had designed and made a recycling bin during a Design Technology class last year, and we were planning on using its design during our Project week. Before the May break, we all consistently met and came together to discuss what exactly our action plan would be, as we wanted to ensure we made full use of the time we had. During these meetings, and after much discussion and collaborative work, we created the following vague action plan for us to follow.\n\n<strong>Day 1:</strong> Spend most of the day going to GAMMA and selecting/finding wood. After this is completed will return to school and spend the rest of the day cutting everything down to the correct dimensions. Goal of day: Get all pieces ready for assembly tomorrow.\n<strong>Day 2:</strong> We will start assembling the first bin today. This will probably take till about lunch. Afterwards we will apply the first (base) layer of paint to bin, so that we can divide roles tomorrow.\n\n<strong>Day 3:</strong> Apply first layer of colour paint to the bin. While this dries we will start construction and assembly of both the second and third bin.\n<strong>Day 4:</strong> Apply second layer of paint to first bin, and base layer to bins 2 and 3. Complete construction of the two remaining bins and alternate between applying paint layers. Additionally, file down all the bins and wood to be smooth before display. Clean-up all the mess.\nIn reality we were able to follow this plan somewhat, though at times we slightly deviated from it. This was the first time many of us were creating and designing something of this scale, and as such it took a while for us to fully develop and learn the necessary skills. Also, by bins 2 and 3 we were able to learn from mistakes made in the construction of bin 1, allowing for us to complete them quicker than expected.\n\nOverall, we all learned valuable lessons from this project week experience, ranging from practical skills to lessons on the importance recycling. We were all able to enjoy this week, and are all extremely proud of the end result. We really think these bins will bring about positive change to the school, and are excited to see them in use.\n- WinBin team 2016\n\n[gallery size=\"medium\" ids=\"568,567,566,565,564,562\"]\n\n&nbsp;', 'Win Bin Maastricht', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'may16-win-bin-maastricht', '', '', '2017-06-23 10:06:05', '2017-06-23 10:06:05', '', 0, 'http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/?p=553', 0, 'post', '', 0),
