(770, 1, '2017-06-23 09:10:34', '2017-06-23 09:10:34', 'The project has been done starts from 25<sup>th</sup>&nbsp;of April until 29<sup>th</sup>&nbsp;of April, and it was basically activities with Orphans youth from the age 15 years to 18, at the organisation called \"Bridge of mercy\" in the city of Sarajevo and some other students came from Zenica. The first day was a presentation from me to the organization about the UWCM, and my personal experience for a year here at UWCM, followed by a&nbsp;presentation from the organization about how it works and their project, and it end up by some activities to get to know to students that I will be working with.<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/pwr4.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-751\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-751 size-large\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/pwr4-e1494423527618-1024x768.jpg\" alt=\"pwr4\" width=\"700\" height=\"525\"></a>\r\n\r\nThe second day was the trip to UWC Mostar, there were 8 students and me, we arrived at the college at 10:30, and we left at 3:30, me, the organization and the college have done short presentations about our work, and after we went to take a look around the city and to the old bridge. It was really good experience and I was very lucky to be there.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-748 size-full\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/pwr2-e1494423483497.jpg\" alt=\"pwr2\" width=\"1278\" height=\"720\">\r\n\r\nThe third day was the multicultural dinner at my uncle\'s home, and before we played various games, and after all slept over in my uncle\'s house. The next day we woke up so excited to do the Holy day, but it was so cold, then it was snowing, so we cancelled the Holy day, and instead, I took them to the Cinema and we watched the film (The Fate of the Furious).\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/pwr3.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-750\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-750\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/pwr3.jpg\" alt=\"pwr3\" width=\"1378\" height=\"1032\"></a>\r\n\r\nIn the 29<sup>th</sup> of April I left Bosnia by bus, the journey took 26 hours, passing Croatia, Slovenia, Austria, Germany to the Netherlands, it was such a nice experience from the beginning to the end, and I advise everyone to do something new with people you do not know in a place you have not visited before. This is the true value of the project week, and I learnt a lot of things in only five days: the good management except catch-up the bus, because I missed my bus to Bosnia, and the only option was to fly, and how to do things and work with new people without any help, and the students were not strong in English.', 'Bosnia: The orphans are no longer alone', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '747-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-06-23 09:10:34', '2017-06-23 09:10:34', '', 747, 'http://localhost/project_week/2017/06/23/747-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(771, 1, '2017-06-23 09:11:25', '2017-06-23 09:11:25', '<b>FIRST DAY OF THE ADVENTURE </b>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">When we arrived in Slovakia, the first thing we noticed is that the diversity was very different from The Netherlands. We arrived at the house in Štefanová and unpacked our things at 8 pm. We were all really excited to explore the nature because it was so green and there was a lot of snow; some of our other friends experienced snow for the very first time. It was so nice to just see the happiness on their faces and see them enjoy the snow; we obviously had a snowball fight… we were all very tired and decided to sleep, for a long time…</span>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/pwsk1.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-742\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-742\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/pwsk1.png\" alt=\"pwsk1\" width=\"691\" height=\"406\"></a>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The next day, some of us hiked to a hill nearby with snow on it while waiting for the others to come back from grocery shopping. It was a lot of fun to casually have a walk in the, already on the first day, stunning surroundings of nature. We took our cameras and made pictures of each other and of the flowers, nature, and landscape around us; of course, we had time for a snowball fight in between! We already noticed that there was a lot of mud and made a lot of jokes about all the possible ways that we would get completely drenched in mud/water; little did we know...</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">When we were settled in and the groceries had been done, we decided to do our first hike. The hike we did was a hike that ended up going to potentially 1200m height. We started the hike in the part which wasn’t completely snow-ified and had a lot of grass and diverse variety of plants. This quickly changed once we got higher in the mountains, where a lot of snow (+- 35 cm) was to be seen literally everywhere we walked. We all really enjoyed playing in the snow and we were really fascinated by the amazing views that Slovakia offered. We went from high to low, from cold to warm, from saturated to hungry. &nbsp;</span>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/pwsk5.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-743\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-743\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/pwsk5.png\" alt=\"pwsk5\" width=\"637\" height=\"467\"></a>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">We ended up walking at 8 pm, in the dark, freezing to death, not knowing exactly where we were going, to get back to Štefanová. There were mostly pine trees in the top of the hike and in the lower parts we could find a variety of small flowers, grouped up together in patches spread over the landscape. The higher we got, the lesser plants grew which could withstand the cold.</span>\r\n\r\n<b>[spacer height=\"20px\"]SECOND DAY</b>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The second day a lot of the snow had gone and we decided to take a shorter more low-lying hike. We went on a hike that went near a waterfall and didn’t have any snow that we had to walk through (which was a pretty nice change after yesterday, which were swimming in the snow). During this hike, we explored a lot more of the forest area of Slovakia. Similarly, to the first part of the hike of the previous day, during this hike we saw a lot of different, and might we say beautiful, flowers grouped up together in patches and a diversity in where they grow. The nature was clearly appreciated in Slovakia, as there were a couple of signs that mentioned that the nature is protected and pollution is punishable, for the greater good of the environment.</span>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/pwsk3.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-740\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-740\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/pwsk3.png\" alt=\"pwsk3\" width=\"634\" height=\"417\"></a> <a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/pwsk4.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-739\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-739\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/pwsk4.png\" alt=\"pwsk4\" width=\"598\" height=\"396\"></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>[spacer height=\"20px\"]THIRD DAY</b>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">On the third day, we decided to step up our game again, we went even higher than on Monday. Today we climbed a hill, which showed the same diversity when it comes to plants and flowers. One thing that struck us was that when we went to an open field at a lower altitude, we could see a lot of small colourful flowers. However, when we went to some open plains at a higher altitude where the wind blew very harshly and viciously, the number of flowers was pretty much none.</span>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/pwsk2.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-741\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-741\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/pwsk2.png\" alt=\"pwsk2\" width=\"588\" height=\"391\"></a>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Tomorrow we are packing our stuff and the day after, we’re going back to Prague and eventually the same evening we are going back to school. Before this, we are going to the Garden of Tereza’s grandparents, to help them do gardening and serve the community while we are at it. </span>\r\n\r\n<b>[spacer height=\"20px\"]LAST DAY</b>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Today we went to the grandparents, with the plan to help them maintain their garden for them as an exchange for helping us with a lot of stuff when coming and staying in Slovakia. Unfortunately, the weather got the better of us and it started raining continuously from the moment we arrived until the middle of the night; this did not kill the spirit of our group, nothing does for that matter, and we decided to sit inside and join the grandparents who cooked food for us, traditional Slovak obviously. It was absolutely, stunningly, overwhelmingly, gorgeously good food; on this we could all agree. It started with traditionally made goulash with some sort of steamed bread, followed by numerous amounts of offers for wine. We immediately noticed that it was not common to decline the offer. An interesting thing we noticed was that alcohol plays a much bigger part in social structures of families and friends than in Western-Europe. In Slovakia, the offer for alcohol is not really for you to decide whether you’d like some alcohol, but for them to offer you the drink. After declining the drink they actually didn’t really understand what we were doing, it was so uncommon. In Western-Europe you offer someone the drink because they want a glass of wine; here, one offers the wine as a gesture of kindness, declining shows a disrespect for their kindness. We were, through the help of Tereza, able to explain that it was definitely not the case!</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">After this, we sat on the couch and played some card games while socializing with the grandparents. It was really nice to see that especially the grandfather wanted to really talk about our nationalities; for example, Amsterdam – Ajax, Cameroon – He had a study friend from there, etc. It was really sweet of them to be so involved with us, and we told them we greatly appreciated their kindness and openheartedness.</span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">We learned during this trip that dedication and perseverance is a key challenge that a lot of us had to overcome because there were times where we were exhausted but had to keep going, and we are proud and grateful of our group that we really helped each other and were very thoughtful of each other when it came to the challenges that each of us had to overcome. There are always going to be things which you cannot change, you must adapt. And that is exactly the thing that we learned on this trip. You cannot control the rain, the temperature, the light. All of this is for us as a group to adapt to and overcome these things. Once done, it is the most satisfying thing to be on that hill, or to be on that mountain, to have crossed that river, to come home on time, to be able to make that meal. All of this shapes us, and all of it contributed to an amazing project week full of experience and joy. This was not only a UWC experience, it was also the trip where we gained memories for life!</span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Celestial bouquets - Slovakia', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '738-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-06-23 09:11:25', '2017-06-23 09:11:25', '', 738, 'http://localhost/project_week/2017/06/23/738-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(772, 1, '2017-06-23 09:12:00', '2017-06-23 09:12:00', '<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">During Easter, my friend, Muaad, and I devoted our time to work on our Youth Social Entrepreneurship, Musicadeau. We did so in hopes of Musicadeau becoming a reality in the next school year. </span>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/musicadeau.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-736\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-736\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/musicadeau.png\" alt=\"musicadeau\" width=\"651\" height=\"236\"></a>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">In essence, Musicadeau will become a one-day event where we invite amateur bands from respectively United World College Maastricht, local high schools and Maastricht University to perform at an external venue. The purpose of this event is to support an NGO with the profit we will gain from the event. Also, to give small and upcoming bands a chance to play in front of an audience. It is quite a task to establish this event and therefore it was needed for us to use the considerable time for planning it. This project week allowed us to do so. We managed to work on the logistical challenges such as which venue to contact, how to advertise the event. Furthermore, we worked on the budgetary aspect of the event. Many expected and unexpected costs came up through our research and work. We finished the schedule of the event itself. Now, we seem ready to pitch our YSE project on May the 3</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">rd</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. Hopefully, this project week has given us an advantage when pitching our project. </span>', 'Musicadeau', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '734-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-06-23 09:12:00', '2017-06-23 09:12:00', '', 734, 'http://localhost/project_week/2017/06/23/734-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(773, 1, '2017-06-23 09:12:34', '2017-06-23 09:12:34', 'In essence, it is a time for students to spend a designated amount of hours a day helping a community, organisation or a target group of a choice to improve their overall work dynamics. In most cases, the point of this activity is that both parties will benefit in a way, whether it would be long-lasting or respectively short-term.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-726\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/pw-mira.jpg\" alt=\"pw mira\" width=\"510\" height=\"907\">\r\n\r\nMy project week took place in between the dates of 27<sup>th</sup> of February and 3<sup>rd</sup> of March in Manchester College’s library, part of the University of Oxford. They working hours I and the head of the library agreed on was 7 hours a day, starting at 9 am with an hour for lunch break and finishing at 5 pm. A very curious fact I hot to learn about the institution itself was that this is, in reality, the smallest college in Oxford out all of them it is equipped with the 6<sup>th </sup>biggest college library amongst them.\r\n\r\n[spacer height=\"10px\"]\r\n\r\nOn my first day I was very puzzled with the fact there are only two permanent persons working the 60,000 books library, but I soon realised that a practice for them is to attract volunteers who come and go and help them manage the workload. Moreover, a common practice is to have a cataloger who joins them every week but is not part of the everyday work dynamics. At the beginning of the very first day, they introduced me to the rest of the people working the college itself during the lunch break which took place in the dining hall. My first day’s&nbsp; job if you want to call it this way consisted mainly of relabeling books in order for them to meet the international agreed on code, which appears to be easier for students to understand since is the same in most libraries. As it turned out this is not an easy task and a proof for this was the number of months it took them to only partially finish the project, which started in the summer of last year.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-727\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/pw-mira2.jpg\" alt=\"pw mira2\" width=\"982\" height=\"552\">\r\n\r\nOver the week I got to do a variety of tasks, from relabeling books, to selling second copies on amazon and describing the series the library had, but no longer needed. This is a method they use in order to get rid of the things they are not interested in and simultaneously make shelf-space for the requested books by the students from the university.\r\n\r\n[spacer height=\"10px\"]\r\n\r\nOn another note, the route I took from Maastricht to Oxford, I did with a train from Maastricht train station to Brussels-midi, from where I got a train to London (Eurostar, therefore I had to go through security and be there an hour in advance). After arriving at the London train station, one should take a subway for 4 stops in order to catch the OxfordTube which will take them to Oxford.', 'Manchester College in University of Oxford  (Tate Library)', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '725-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-06-23 09:12:34', '2017-06-23 09:12:34', '', 725, 'http://localhost/project_week/2017/06/23/725-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(774, 1, '2017-06-23 09:13:11', '2017-06-23 09:13:11', '&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThis is an art based project in Paris and we will explore the different arts in museums and street arts. It will also focus on how does the refugee crisis in Europe impact the newly created art (if there are any). We will interview one artists with different age group, and some the refugees.\r\n\r\n[spacer height=\"10px\"]\r\n\r\nIn our first day we visited museum ‘’Musee du Montmartre’’, according to the website it supposed to be an old museum but after we went there we could not find any art from the 16 or 17 century. Therefore, we counted it as a modern one.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-716\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/20170302_134838-1.jpg\" alt=\"20170302_134838\" width=\"2576\" height=\"1932\">\r\n\r\nIn our second day, we had to visit the second biggest and popular museum in Paris ‘’musee de orsay’’. But the challenge was in finding the way to get there. We took the Metro, but the wrong one. However, after we spend two hours to reach it, we also had to wait for almost one and half other hour in the line to get there.&nbsp; It was a very famous old museum and we got to see a lot of old art from many artiest French and non-French. We got more idea about art in Paris’s museums and about Paris itself. As every evening we were giving our self a chance to go out and explore Paris. We visiting some popular tourist places in Paris like the tower and the Notre dame cathedral.<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/20170302_134838.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-715\">\r\n</a>[spacer height=\"10px\"]\r\n\r\nWe used to visit museums every day, even the day we supposed to visit the artist and interview her. In the third day we interviewed the artiest and we recorded the interview. She was originally from Iran, but migrate to France 25 years ago, and she graduated from an art university in France. Today she is an art teacher and she has a small studio and she teaches in her own way, because there are many things she doesn’t agree with the other French way of teaching art. The questions were about her journey in the art field and what are the changes that she has realized in the Modern art and what are the challenges she faces as an artist in Paris. The interview was an open conversation that we recorded.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-717\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/20170227_122535.jpg\" alt=\"20170227_122535\" width=\"3264\" height=\"1836\">\r\n\r\nIn our last day, we visited the Louvre, and it was much huger than we expected. We saw so many old art from the 16th and 17<sup>th</sup>, but of course we couldn’t finish quarter of it.\r\n\r\n[spacer height=\"10px\"]\r\n\r\nIf we will give a summary about the different between the old and modern art and how technology influence the modern art in Paris. In the 16<sup>th</sup> and 17<sup>th</sup> most of the arts were a religious based art and most of them seemed to have the same colours. While the modern art have different ways of using the colours and the idea of exhibitions is much used. The arties said that she is also a singer, she 10 years ago she came up with an idea of painting while she is singing, and she wanted to spread it Paris and teach it for the new generation, but sadly she was not allowed to do it because there was no references for it. That is why she said ‘’ In Paris the mother of art city, they don’t allowed you to create any art, you just have to copy what was already there, and I don’t consider this as a modern art.’’[spacer height=\"10px\"]\r\n\r\nWe also failed to find any street art in Paris, the government does not allowed that because they want to keep the city as historical as it is. We also asked the arties about refugee and how if there are any opportunities for them in the art field, but the answer was an expected. She said in Paris people don’t care how brave you are in your art work and idea unless you are from a developed countries like, America, Netherlands, and Italy….so on. Therefore, refugees here have no chances at all until now. She said ‘’ even me who came here 25 years ago, I got rejected from many chances because I am from Iran’’.\r\n\r\n[spacer height=\"10px\"]\r\n\r\nOne thing we did not like about Paris was the traffic, to some extent it was very risky and unorganised, people don’t care about the traffic light at all, even if it is time for walker to pass cars will still keep going. We also felt the city was resist somehow, in some areas we observed that there were only Arab people, and in other only black people. As there were so many homeless people everywhere.&nbsp; But the people in general were very nice and helpful, many people were advising us to be careful and to take care of our self and properties, and they were helping us to find our way.\r\n\r\n[spacer height=\"10px\"]\r\n\r\nIn conclusion, we learnt a lot from this project. We get to know each other more by dividing the work between us, each of us learned something new. For example Rabab learnt how to cook, Hoza and Len learned how to read physical maps. We learned about the refugee in the art field, some French cultures and a lot about art in the mother of art city. &nbsp;Some of us already planned their next project that will be focused on the refugee homeless in Paris.\r\n\r\n[spacer height=\"10px\"]\r\n\r\nWe faced so many challenges to achieve this project, but we were all patient and by encouraging each other we were able to make it.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Art in Paris', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '714-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-06-23 09:13:11', '2017-06-23 09:13:11', '', 714, 'http://localhost/project_week/2017/06/23/714-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(775, 1, '2017-06-23 09:13:45', '2017-06-23 09:13:45', '<strong>Stefano Santori, Ana Santos, Alex Belo, Camila Lindo, Asbjorn Hansen</strong>\r\n\r\n[spacer height=\"10px\"]\r\n<h3>Design and pursue a student-led project</h3>\r\nWe had very little help from adults, which was a challenge. We had to be responsible enough to be able to fulfil the objectives of the project week and to keep engaging with the community even when things weren’t on our side. As students, we end up messing up and making mistakes, but those make us grow up and learn way more than if everything turned out alright with very little to almost no challenge. I can say on behalf of the whole group that we learned so much and we grew so much from the 5 days we spent in Prague.\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n<h3>Provide a service to an organization/community.</h3>\r\nAlthough we did not manage to work with the hospital we went one day to volunteer in an orphanage to paint the walls of a room and in another day we made sandwiches and distributed them to the homeless people in Prague. This made me realise that although these small actions will not make a big difference in the orphanage and will not end homelessness in Prague they help and make people keep a smile on their faces as being helped is always an enjoyable experience.\r\n\r\n<em>&nbsp;<img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-703\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/pw01.jpg\" alt=\"pw01\" width=\"1334\" height=\"1000\"></em>\r\n<h6 style=\"text-align: center;\"><em>The making of the sandwiches </em></h6>\r\n<h3><em>&nbsp;</em>Organise activities outside the campus</h3>\r\nThe biggest conclusion that I took from helping to organise a project week is that things might not go as expected. The process itself of organising activities is a bit challenging as I had to come up with ideas of activities to entertain patients in the hospital such as playing the guitar.&nbsp; But the most challenging part was to come up with activities to help the community when the hospital denied us a chance to work with them. Nevertheless, in the end, we come up with the idea of distributing sandwiches to homeless people in Prague and that was probably as rewarding as helping others\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-704 size-medium\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/pw02-225x300.jpg\" alt=\"pw02\" width=\"225\" height=\"300\">\r\n<h6 style=\"text-align: center;\">Giving sandwiches to the homeless</h6>\r\n<h3>Explore a new country and culture</h3>\r\nSince the very beginning, we understood that Prague was going to be an unexpected beauty. The small streets surrounded by coloured buildings that opened themselves in stunning squares with architectures from the Italian renaissance. Hospitable smiles from the locals in the small cafes and light happiness while crossing the famous bridge with our eyes full of the cathedral’s peaks are the things that we’ll remember the most.\r\n<h3>Improve your organisation, communication and collaboration skills</h3>\r\nThe project week was a great way to really understand what life ends up being like. Things don’t work out, there are miscommunications and we have to learn how to turn those problems around. The week we were in Prague we were met with multiple challenges, people that only spoke Czech, not wanting to collaborate with us. We had to stick as a group and rely on each other. We had to come up with a brand new project week and we did it, as a team.\r\n<h3>Get to know more about yourself and your group</h3>\r\nWalking for kilometres in the city created a special bond between us. Talks about how different or similar the city was compared to our cities made us share moments and anecdotes between the group. Shoutout of freedom while watching Prague from the edge of the castle in the late afternoon’s light, a moment of silence and reflection, that won’t leave us for a long time and gave us something with a deeper level of sensation.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/pw01.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-703\">\r\n</a> <a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/pw02.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-704\">\r\n</a> <a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/pw03.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-705\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-705\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/pw03.jpg\" alt=\"pw03\" width=\"2048\" height=\"1365\"></a>\r\n<h6 style=\"text-align: center;\"><em>Prague from the castle</em></h6>\r\n<h6 style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</h6>\r\n<h3 style=\"text-align: left;\">Achieve a positive (social) change</h3>\r\nSince the NGO working with the hospital, ended up not wanting to collaborate with us we decided to go around the city and help the homeless. Distributing sandwiches in hopes of making their day better and brighter. The smiles we got, the “thank you” was something that warmed all of our hearts and I believe will stay with us. We were able to, hopefully, helped those people a little. Big changes start with small actions.', 'Prague II.', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '702-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-06-23 09:13:45', '2017-06-23 09:13:45', '', 702, 'http://localhost/project_week/2017/06/23/702-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(776, 1, '2017-06-23 09:14:09', '2017-06-23 09:14:09', 'Our project week group consist of Arabi, Martha, Marion, Alejo, Tereza, Sydney, Zaafir, Jeremiah, Yi Wynn, and Abdul. We conducted this project week based on the idea from Tereza a native of the Czech Republic. The Kangaroo Orphanage is a halfway house of sorts where children are placed until they either are moved to a permanent long term orphanage or the court awards a guardian custody. The House was a somewhat beautiful light in something that when you pause and think is a very sad situation. With Tereza as our Guide, we undertook a variety of challenges and learning objectives. The ones we followed were:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Design and pursue a student-led project.</li>\r\n 	<li>Provide a service to an organization/community.</li>\r\n 	<li>Organize activities outside the campus.</li>\r\n 	<li>Explore a new country and culture.</li>\r\n 	<li>Improve your organisation, communication and collaboration skills.</li>\r\n 	<li>Get to know more about yourself and your group.</li>\r\n 	<li>Achieve a positive (social) change.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nWe achieved the first goal of designing and pursuing a student-led project. By planning this project we fulfil this first goal. With Tereza, a native of Prague,&nbsp; at the helm of the designing the project we arranged times and dates to go to the orphanage along with how to get from our Airbnb to the orphanage which was out of walking distance, to say the least being two metro changes and two buses away. We pre-arrange our service activities at the orphanage where needed and they requested that we play&nbsp; with the young kids and paint in the morning and the entire group playing games and telling the older children, now returned from school, about our countries.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-697\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/PW-prague.jpg\" alt=\"PW prague\" width=\"2500\" height=\"1666\">\r\n\r\nWe explored the goal of organising activities outside the campus which proved to be quite the challenge because one has to account for not only age but also language. Most children spoke little English if any at all and we found ourself at the time heavily leaning on Tereza for what we called “English Subtitles” for the insistent Czech chatter. The activities we organised were talking about our countries, Argentinian Dance courtesy of our Argentinian Alejo, Frisbee, tag, hide and seek, and also a Czech game the children taught us called vybika. We also participated in some activities which the children came up with like horse where we had children on our back for much of the play time along with a particularly delightful talent show with beautiful songs by the children, all of which Tereza told us later were about love and some about how lovers leave and abandon the. We were perplexed, to say the least. The children also learned new words along the way like numbers, introductory phrase, ‘high five’ and “come tomorrow’ which broke all of the hearts on our last day.\r\n\r\nWe also got the opportunity to explore Prague and the Culture visiting Prague Castle, the national museum, Charles bridge, john Lennon wall, and the escape room famous in Eastern Europe. We even manage to taste some traditional Czech food and learn a few works like “Ahoy!’ And ‘Diki’. We also picked up some historical and architectural aspects of Prague from a tour we accidentally end up following. The goal of Improving our organisation, communication and collaboration skills was by our largest area by far.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/prague-pw-2.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-698\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-698\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/prague-pw-2.jpg\" alt=\"prague pw 2\" width=\"2500\" height=\"1667\"></a>\r\n\r\nWith ten people every length of the journey requires organisational skills. From food to finding a balance between meeting the wants of each individual and the group as well. With meeting every night we manage to untangle who would cook dinner each night since it was cheaper, and bedroom arrangements. When we met a decision that not all agreed on a discussion was conducted allowing for everyone who wished to express themselves\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-700\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/pw-prague.jpg\" alt=\"pw prague\" width=\"2500\" height=\"1667\">\r\n\r\nFor me, I learned that in a group setting with 15 people leaving with a flat I learned that personally at times it\'s good to take time for yourself to get air to breathe and simple stop and take in the moment that you are alive and in this vibrant and eclectic city. I learned that in my group role assignment was important because it allowed for tasked to be shared and organisation.\r\nIn conclusion, The end result of a project week is to make some impact in the society within which you are operating. For us, I believe the impact we made is giving the children exposure to people from a variety of places, races, languages, and ethnicities. In what another part of their life will they get to meet or see a Syrian, a Malaysian and a Bahamian in the same room. In a place where they have one map which still had Yugoslavia on it; exposure to these different peoples in a positive environment can leave a lasting impression.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nDiky Praha!', 'Feb\'17 - Prague I., the Kangaroo Orphanage', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '696-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-06-23 09:14:09', '2017-06-23 09:14:09', '', 696, 'http://localhost/project_week/2017/06/23/696-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
