(781, 1, '2017-06-23 09:16:12', '2017-06-23 09:16:12', 'The project week at AZC Maastricht started rather rough for 6 of our students, coming from 5 countries- Syria, Palestine, Morocco, Bulgaria and France. However, in the first days we established the genuine need for such a project in a place such as AZC Maastricht- The refugee&nbsp;center in Maastricht.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/servethecity.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-660\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-660\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/servethecity.png\" alt=\"servethecity\" width=\"754\" height=\"435\"></a>\r\n\r\nIn the beginning couple of days, we attempted to inquire into the true needs and perhaps preferences of the people we started to meet at the refugee center. Through very personal contacts and conversations, we established that the main need for the people there was something in the form of activities that would make their day less gray and make them happier each day in order to decrease the prolonged time that they have to spend often away from their families through having fun in the form of activities and listening to their diverse and very interesting stories.\r\nWe succeeded in diversifying their quotidian and making sure that they would spend their time in a slightly different way than the one they have had before through sports tournaments, group discussions, group activities&nbsp;such as cooking or just walking. Such activities reached our set objective and helped to us to develop our personality and mindset.\r\nThe values that we had in mind for our project, and the mission we wanted to fulfil were similar to the ones of UWC.\r\n\r\nWith values such as compassion and service, mutual responsibility and respect and many other UWC Values, we started our project week full of enthusiasm to help others,\r\nEach value played a big role in our work and helped influencing the way we deal with people in AZC, and the fact that we were able to share those values was very uplifting for us and was an achievement by itself.\r\nThe outcome was quite satisfying as well as we managed to meet most of the objectives that we had set previously.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/servethecity2.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-662\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-662\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/servethecity2.png\" alt=\"servethecity2\" width=\"679\" height=\"429\"></a> <a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/servethecity1.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-661\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-661\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/servethecity1.png\" alt=\"servethecity1\" width=\"637\" height=\"407\"></a>', 'Serve the City', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '659-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-06-23 09:16:12', '2017-06-23 09:16:12', '', 659, 'http://localhost/project_week/2017/06/23/659-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(782, 1, '2017-06-23 09:16:37', '2017-06-23 09:16:37', '<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Why was there a genuine need for the PW?</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">English Childcare opened very recently and as a newborn daycare, they needed a lot of equipment and infrastructure in order to have an optimal environment for the kids. We thought that it was a good and constructive idea to help them build the equipment they needed, especially when the growth of kids of different range of years is in play. Furthermore, the Childcare has financial limits as well and they need to reconstruct and redesign the interior and exterior of the host house, prioritizing matters of higher importance and taking care of them through financial means.&nbsp;</span>We were able to learn many new skills through completing many tasks, such as building baby cribs, building an entire garden for vegetables out of nothing, sandpits, did a football court and redefined the aesthetics of a garden maze. Furthermore, we learnt how to deal with kids of many ages and especially many personalities. We have also bound with the staff of English Childcare, because they were very open to us and chose tasks adapted to our needs and limits.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-656\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/child.png\" alt=\"child\" width=\"702\" height=\"524\">\r\n\r\nOur project week links with the UWC mission mainly in these points: international and intercultural understanding, as the range of nationalities of the kids is very ample and come from different cultural backgrounds (most of them come from UWC primary section). Personal responsibility and integrity, as taking care and work for a daycare is a huge responsibility as the safety of kids is the focus. Compassion and service is of central importance because our work there is unpaid and without any second aims; just helping some people in need.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/child.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-656\">\r\n</a> <a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/child1.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-657\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-657\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/child1.png\" alt=\"child1\" width=\"708\" height=\"531\"></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'English Childcare', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '655-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-06-23 09:16:37', '2017-06-23 09:16:37', '', 655, 'http://localhost/project_week/2017/06/23/655-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(783, 1, '2017-06-23 09:17:00', '2017-06-23 09:17:00', '<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Our project consisted of a peer-support training programme. Peer supporters are a group of students that other students can approach and talk to without a fear of being judged or gossiped about. We believe that everyone in the UWC community needs someone to talk to without worrying about these things.This is because of the huge amount of stress in the DP programme and also for many people the great change faced when joining this school. This largely impacts the psychological well-being of the students and the peer supporters can help relieve that stress or deal with it.</span>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/20160623_112242.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-651\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-651\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/20160623_112242.jpg\" alt=\"20160623_112242\" width=\"3264\" height=\"1836\"></a>\r\n\r\nThroughout the project week we bonded as a group, we achieved this through different off campus activities (such as yoga and hiking) as well as cooking and eating as a group. The training sessions took place in the mornings of Wednesday. Thursday and Friday, and the afternoon of Monday. In those we acquired theoretical knowledge and we got to practice it with each other while preparing to become peer supporters the whole of the community next year. While reflecting on the project week activities we recognised how we came across many values. At first, empathy and understanding are a key element of peer support as they allow us to see facts from the other person’s point of view, helping us to listen in an objective manner and to create a non-judgemental environment.\r\n\r\nPersonal responsibility and integrity - each of the peer-supporters has the responsibility of keeping the information the other person tells them confidential unless they or the people around them are at risk of harm. Integrity is necessary because it is important that we as peer-supporters don’t lose our individuality because one of our main features is being peers because we are members of the same community collaborating to make it a happier place. Mutual responsibility and respect is therefore also important because of the peer aspect, neither of them are superior to the other.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-653\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/20160627_093436.jpg\" alt=\"20160627_093436\" width=\"1280\" height=\"720\">\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">We will dedicate time to provide this service to our community and through compassion we will be able to achieve empathy and understanding.</span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">We challenged ourselves to learning new skills and at times going out of our comfort zone by opening ourselves up to our fellow peer supporters while practicing.</span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Action and personal example - we think that our action will not only be directly positive for the community but an example for our peers to feel more comfortable in opening themselves.</span>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/20160627_093436.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-653\">\r\n</a> <a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/20160627_0933130.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-652\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-652\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/20160627_0933130.jpg\" alt=\"20160627_093313(0)\" width=\"3264\" height=\"1836\"></a>', 'Peer support training', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '650-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-06-23 09:17:00', '2017-06-23 09:17:00', '', 650, 'http://localhost/project_week/2017/06/23/650-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(784, 1, '2017-06-23 09:17:23', '2017-06-23 09:17:23', 'The Journey Project Maastricht is an initiative designed by UWCM students for the YSE&nbsp;Programme and has since developed into a full June Project Week. It started when the&nbsp;founding students realized that there was a lack of communication and socialization between&nbsp;local Dutch people and the refugees that were in the area, primarily the ones living at the&nbsp;nearby Aziel Zoekers Centrum. Since this led to many misconceptions and negative&nbsp;sentiments, they realized that there was a need to improve this and the result was The&nbsp;Journey, a magazine or book intended to share the stories of refugees at the AZC&nbsp;accompanied by creative pieces done by the refugees themselves. This promotes deeper&nbsp;understanding between people from different cultures now living together and encourages&nbsp;them to treat one another with respect and compassion. As we hope to continue issuing the&nbsp;Journey into the future, we hope that it will improve peaceful intercultural understanding&nbsp;between the two groups both in the present&nbsp;and sustainably into the future.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/thejourney.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-646\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-646 aligncenter\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/thejourney.png\" alt=\"thejourney\" width=\"322\" height=\"423\"></a> <a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/thejourney2.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-647\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-647 alignright\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/thejourney2.png\" alt=\"thejourney2\" width=\"420\" height=\"308\"></a> <a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/thejourney3.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-648\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-648\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/thejourney3.png\" alt=\"thejourney3\" width=\"327\" height=\"436\"></a>\r\n\r\nThroughout our project week we worked&nbsp;with the refugees to start our process of&nbsp;creating a magazine. Our group created&nbsp;flyers to get our project known to the&nbsp;refugees. Many refugees were interested in&nbsp;meeting with us and collaborating on&nbsp;making this magazine. We held interviews&nbsp;with various refugees from different&nbsp;countries and each had a different unique&nbsp;story to tell. This is very benefitting for our&nbsp;magazine as we want our readers to get to&nbsp;know the situations of these refugees and&nbsp;to understand their situation better. After&nbsp;conducting these interviews we wrote them&nbsp;up in a style of a story so that our readers&nbsp;would be more engaged with the stories.&nbsp;To promote the magazine we made a&nbsp;website and a facebook page. We also&nbsp;worked with a local organisation who&nbsp;distribute items to refugees to make their&nbsp;lives more comfortable. This was very&nbsp;successful and the organisation was&nbsp;grateful for our help. Our project week&nbsp;overall was very successful and we&nbsp;enjoyed working with the refugees.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/thejourney4.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-645\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-645\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/thejourney4.png\" alt=\"thejourney4\" width=\"428\" height=\"286\"></a>', 'The Journey', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '644-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-06-23 09:17:23', '2017-06-23 09:17:23', '', 644, 'http://localhost/project_week/2017/06/23/644-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(785, 1, '2017-06-23 09:17:51', '2017-06-23 09:17:51', '<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">During this past week, we have been working on a mural project for the school campus. Our plan was to make a piece of art that was made by the students for the school community. This way we would be celebrating the different cultures of our students whilst creating a colourful and interesting artwork to brighten up the campus.</span>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/artp2.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-642\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-642\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/artp2.png\" alt=\"artp2\" width=\"491\" height=\"363\"></a>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">We wanted this to be a whole school project (ideally with primary and MYP getting involved with the painting) so we asked and used ideas from the staff and students. On the first day we met with students from MYP 2 and, using their different cultural backgrounds, created a list of monuments from around the globe. We then went on to designing, drawing and beginning to paint the final mural. Although we haven’t completely finished the mural, we have made good progress and plan to finish the rest when we return from the summer break.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The purpose of the mural was to visually represent the idea of global peace and intercultural &nbsp;understanding by joining monuments from many cultures - showing how we are a united community. Once finished, we are planning to attach the board along the wall going into the bike sheds. This way students, parents and visitors will be able to experience it when entering the campus.</span>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/artp.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-641\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-641\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/artp.png\" alt=\"artp\" width=\"740\" height=\"367\"></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Art Exploration', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '640-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-06-23 09:17:51', '2017-06-23 09:17:51', '', 640, 'http://localhost/project_week/2017/06/23/640-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(786, 1, '2017-06-23 09:18:22', '2017-06-23 09:18:22', '<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">In our project week we created a map of Maastricht for the DP1s coming in the fall. The map comes in the form of a pamphlet which also contains useful information to the students which are unfamiliar to the city. Our group was made up of three students, two of which are day students and one is a former day student. This allowed us to use a lot of our past knowledge of the city to come up with ideas for the map.</span>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/jv3.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-636\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-636\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/jv3.png\" alt=\"jv3\" width=\"550\" height=\"308\"></a>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">In the picture above, &nbsp;the final version of the map can be seen. This is the main accomplishment of our project week because we had to make a concrete product. It required a lot of planning, and evaluation of what the students required in the map. In order to know what the students needed, we talked to residential students about what they felt in need of. We also had to gather a lot of information on the internet about restaurants, stores, day activities etc. which we included on the other page. However, we had to leave out a lot of information because we felt that it was not vital and we did not have a lot of space. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">While thinking about a possible project week our group was brainstorming what students in our school needed. Last year there was a handbook given out to the students which included a map. Looking at the map, we saw that it could be taken much further and was very lackluster. Therefore we proposed to make a map of Maastricht accompanied by information which could be folded into a pamphlet, so that students can easily carry them. They will be provided to the students by including them in the student hand books created by another project week.</span>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/jv2.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-638\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-638\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/jv2.png\" alt=\"jv2\" width=\"591\" height=\"335\"></a>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Making our project week required us to have a deeper understanding of students needs with regards to their background and culture. Not only did we have to take into account the student\'s needs, but also the environment’s. We made sure to not print more paper than we needed. Since there was little to no supervision of the project week we had to keep ourselves in check throughout the four days. We made sure to take the same breaks as normal days as much as possible so that we did not waste too much time. Overall it was a nice project week with a lot of memorable experiences and fun :)</span>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/jv.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-637\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-637\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/jv.png\" alt=\"jv\" width=\"579\" height=\"321\"></a>', 'Map of Maastricht for new students', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '635-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-06-23 09:18:22', '2017-06-23 09:18:22', '', 635, 'http://localhost/project_week/2017/06/23/635-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(787, 1, '2017-06-23 09:18:45', '2017-06-23 09:18:45', 'Our project aims to act as a start up to the Happiness Club to be organised in school next year. The project will serve as a trial period for us to try out different events and activities and also a chance to implement our ideas. We would also used this project week opportunity to interview people about their thoughts on happiness and the significance of this. We felt that there was a genuine need as we believe that happiness is something simple and beautiful, yet our busy schedules in this boarding and school environment often makes us feel unhappy and forget the importance of being happy and to think positively. And so, the project week and the club aims to promote happiness to the school community (MYP, primary, DP and staff members) through various activities, sessions etc. This project week also gives us time to plan our year schedule for next year’s club.\r\n\r\nWe spent our first day filming the happiness documentary and also planning the MYP session. The second day, we have successfully conducted three MYP sessions (more than planned, MYP 1,2, and 3) during June 23. The focus topic of the day was gratitude, and how by appreciating others we can make others and also ourselves happy. The workshop was our greatest accomplishments as we felt that we were able to get across our message well, and it was interesting to see the different reaction of the activity from the different age groups. The MYP1s, we felt had the most fun, where some of the MYP2s and 3s got emotional during the focus activity, which was very touching and interesting to observe. We also decided to do more of these sessions but with different focus topics to more MYPs, primary, DPs and staff members next year, as we got feedback from the MYPs that they wished they had sessions like this during tutor period. The last 2 days were used to finish the documentary and also planning for next year’s club structure.\r\n\r\nIn this project week, we linked the UWC value of Personal Challenge, as we felt that happiness is simple, but difficult to always be positive, hence it is important to challenge ourselves to see the bright side of what we face in life, and to look deeper and around us to realize the happiness around us and to embrace it. We believe that in order to change the world, we have to change ourselves first! Also, Mutual understanding, as we had to adapt to different age groups for the MYP sessions. And a sense of idealism, for the idea of happiness!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Happiness Project', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '625-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-06-23 09:18:45', '2017-06-23 09:18:45', '', 625, 'http://localhost/project_week/2017/06/23/625-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(788, 1, '2017-06-23 09:19:54', '2017-06-23 09:19:54', '<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Maastricht is only 50km away from the nuclear reactor Tihange located in Belgium. Pressurized water reactors such as Tihange are built to have a lifespan of 30 to 40 years, which means that Tihange should have been shut down in 2012. This however did not happen, its lifespan was even extended to 2025. When there is a serious problem or some kind of damage, the reactor shuts down automatically. Over the past two year it has happened hundreds of times and every single time the Belgian government has re-started it &nbsp;manually. If there is a core meltdown accident, we could face similar consequences as we have experienced with Chernobyl and Fukushima. Carolin and I found that no one in school is informed about this local issue and decided that we want to raise awareness. Our aim is to inform people in order to avoid panic if something should happen, since that would create a disastrous chaos. &nbsp;We have created power point presentation and will be printing leaflets that we want to share with the school community next school year. This will give people a detailed overview of &nbsp;what exactly the issue is, what they should prepare for and how to act in a worst case scenario. We will offer people to come talk to us if they should have any further concerns or are unsure. </span>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/tih1.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-612\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-612\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/tih1.png\" alt=\"tih1\" width=\"769\" height=\"575\"></a> <a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/tih2.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-613\"><img class=\"wp-image-613 size-full aligncenter\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/tih2.png\" alt=\"tih2\" width=\"742\" height=\"491\"></a>&nbsp;<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/tih4.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-615\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-615 size-full\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/tih4.png\" alt=\"tih4\" width=\"451\" height=\"602\"></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nOur PW links to the UWC mission and values in several ways. The UWC mission states “UWC makes education a force to unite people, nations and cultures for peace and <b>a sustainable future</b>”. Sustainability plays a major role in this project, since we have to invest in sustainable energy resources rather than for example nuclear energy, that carries too many risks when not operated correctly. Looking at the nine values, a few stand out: “Mutual responsibility and respect”, “Respect for the environment” and ”Action and personal example”. These apply to our PW as it is our mutual responsibility to consider and act upon these issues as it can only be resolved when people work together and find solutions. Respect for the environment it very obvious as the environment would majorly suffer under a core meltdown. Action is needed in the resolution of this issue and Carolin and I have taken part in the demonstration (personal example) and are planning on signing the petition &nbsp;(min. Age 18). Thus, all three values apply.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-614 size-full\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/tih3.png\" alt=\"tih3\" width=\"743\" height=\"563\">', 'The nuclear reactor Tihange in Belgium', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '611-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-06-23 09:19:54', '2017-06-23 09:19:54', '', 611, 'http://localhost/project_week/2017/06/23/611-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(789, 1, '2017-06-23 09:27:19', '2017-06-23 09:27:19', 'During our project we spend our time repairing the residential/school bicycles. This would benefit the school community due to the fact that students arriving next school year for DP1 will have transport to for example the city of Maastricht. This will also benefit the soon to be DP2’s because over the course of the year they might have run in to some problems with their bicycle which we repaired so that they can also have a fresh start at the beginning of the next school year, Transport wise. What we’ve accomplished during this project week is that we tried our at most to repair the damaged/nonworking bicycles. This means: Replacing the inner tube, gluing the inner tube, oiling the chain + breaks, filling up the tires, reattaching breaks, wheels, locks, fenders etc. As we are not bicycle experts we lacked some knowledge thus the fact being we were also giving a limited amount of tools and funding to fully repair the residential bicycle. For example on some bicycles the wheel was bend which means that the bicycle did not function. We would have to purchase an entire new wheel in order to fix this problem. A very common issue we ran into was that more then 1/3 of the bicycles had missing keys meaning that the level of repairing on those specific bicycles was very limited. We could only tire pressure and if all the parts were firm.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-603 size-full\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/bike1.png\" alt=\"bike1\" width=\"712\" height=\"283\">\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/bike2.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-604\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-604 size-full\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/bike2.png\" alt=\"bike2\" width=\"708\" height=\"311\"></a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/bike3.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-605\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-605 size-full\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/bike3.png\" alt=\"bike3\" width=\"714\" height=\"311\"></a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/bike4.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-606\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-606 size-full\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/bike4.png\" alt=\"bike4\" width=\"711\" height=\"312\"></a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/bike5.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-607\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-607 size-full\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/bike5.png\" alt=\"bike5\" width=\"710\" height=\"312\"></a>\r\n\r\nOverall it was a good experience and our project has shown a clear link between the mission and the values of UWC. By creating safer and better transport for the students we also created more learning opportunities. Also by improving the school owned bicycles we can promote the use of this way of environmentally friendly transport. Everyone got along and got treated with patience and respect. Therefore we learned to cooperate with each other. It was of course also a personal challenge for everyone on the team because not everyone was as well known with bicycles as the other. In conclusion taking the lack of tools and other items such as keys and spare parts into consideration it was quite successful.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nBy Tristan', 'Bike repair group', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '602-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-06-23 09:27:19', '2017-06-23 09:27:19', '', 602, 'http://localhost/project_week/2017/06/23/602-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(790, 1, '2017-06-23 09:32:16', '2017-06-23 09:32:16', 'For the past 4 days, our group had an intensive yet super fun time learning different writing techniques to help people next year.\r\n\r\nTo be honest, at first I doubted my abilities in writing. Coming to UWC and taking up IB was challenging for me in terms of having so many essay-based subjects. Yet after workshops with Larissa and Johannes, I realize I am very privileged to be able to speak English fluently and convey my intended message with ease. This project week is basically preparing us to set up a writing support team.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-627\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/File_001.jpeg\" alt=\"File_001\" width=\"3264\" height=\"2448\">\r\n\r\nWhy did this all start? Well, in our community, we have quite diverse English levels. We have a very wide range of English speakers, ranging from native speakers to people who have never spoken a word of English until 1 month before they come. Since at UWCM, we do the IB in English. From what we see from our friends and peers to our very personal experience, we feel that there is not enough support for writing in general, especially when IB is such an ‘essay based’ curriculum. Hopefully, after this intensive kind of short course, we can establish a writing support team to help students with any kind of problem with writing in any subjects.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-628\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/File_006.jpeg\" alt=\"File_006\" width=\"3264\" height=\"2448\">\r\n\r\nThroughout the course of the project week, I myself took a lot away from what Larissa and Johannes presented. Larissa focussed on the technical parts for writing an essay especially for English A students, while Johannes highlighted the needs of students who take English acquisition. In order for the support group to work, we really have to cater for needs of different individuals, exploring the differences between a native speaker and a non-native and how to approach them were particularly useful. It is also very important to be empathetic. We’ve all been through different struggles on our road of learning, we want them to feel safe and positive when coming to us, it id only by them feeling safe to share their work then we can all learn and improve.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter size-large wp-image-629\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/File_008-1024x768.jpeg\" alt=\"File_008\" width=\"700\" height=\"525\">\r\n\r\nAll in all, it was a very fruitful and intensive project week. I hope we could all make the writing support a reality next year!\r\n\r\nIt will be all WRITE!\r\n\r\nWritten by Melody Lam.', 'Writing support group', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '600-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-06-23 09:32:16', '2017-06-23 09:32:16', '', 600, 'http://localhost/project_week/2017/06/23/600-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(791, 1, '2017-06-23 09:32:53', '2017-06-23 09:32:53', 'It all started with takecarebnb, an organization based in Amsterdam that helped refugees to find local host families. We were all excited to work with them until we found out one day before that there had been a huge miscommunication with them since the early start of the collaboration with them. We were all worried about what was going on. Since it was very late we did not have many options to choose from so the only option possible was the animal farm. Some of us were not so enthusiastic because of the fear of being around animals, however we were determined to accomplish the project week so we undertook the challenge.\n\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/animal-farm.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-593\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-593 size-full\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/animal-farm.png\" alt=\"animal farm\" width=\"601\" height=\"359\" /></a>\n\nThe first day was quite hard physical work cutting tree branches and transporting them and by the end of the day we were all very tired. Also we realized that we needed to communicate more effectively with the owners and workers in the farm when we wanted to share our feelings about a certain task given to us. On the second day the temperatures were quite high and for some of us that were fasting this proved to be very challenging. The task on the second day was cutting grass and cleaning the goat barn and the inside of the main facility. By the third day all of us got more used to the kind of work done in the farm so for all of us it felt easier. It is certain that for all the of us it was not the most enjoyable way we could have spent three days and not the ideal project week but there was need for that work to be done and we did learn a lot throughout the process. We learned about efficient communication, how to work better as a group, punctuality, perseverance.\n\nby Gisela, Sophie, Holly, Helen, Nina, Nelson and Omnia', 'Takecarebnb --> Kinderboerderij De Heeg', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '592-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-06-23 09:32:53', '2017-06-23 09:32:53', '', 592, 'http://localhost/project_week/2017/06/23/592-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(792, 1, '2017-06-23 09:33:03', '2017-06-23 09:33:03', '<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Our Project Week was to continue with the idea of the Student Handbook that was started last year by two past students. Last year this handbook was really helpful for new students to have all the most important information in one place, although there were some flaws in the book. So our idea was to create another Student Handbook in a new format that will be applicable for all students with different levels of English. Also another problem that we have discovered with the previous handbook was that it was given only to the residential students, leaving day students with no information. That’s why in our booklet we covered topics that are related to residential students but also some for day students, so they will also find this handbook useful next year.</span>\n\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-590 size-full\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/student-booklet.png\" alt=\"student booklet\" width=\"782\" height=\"438\" />\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">During this four days we managed to create new Student Handbook. We divided work between the four of us, so each person was responsible for different part of the student handbook. Before we started writing we did a little research to see what other students thought about the last years handbook, what was good and what would that change. Based on that we did an outline of our student handbook and then we were just writing. We met regularly to check each other progress and finally put everything we got together to create a completely new Student Handbook.\nOur Project Week for sure relates to the UWC value <b>Compassion and Service, because we created something for our school that hopefully will be useful next year for new students.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">by Jeremiah, Clara, Wiktoria &amp; Michalina</span>', 'Student Handbook', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '589-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-06-23 09:33:03', '2017-06-23 09:33:03', '', 589, 'http://localhost/project_week/2017/06/23/589-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(793, 1, '2017-06-23 09:33:14', '2017-06-23 09:33:14', 'During the June Project Week our team has been working on the Refugee welcome guide. The Guide has been created in order to help the refugees in finding the cheapest places in town. The first day we met two women from the refugee camp, where they shared with us their first experiences and how difficult it has been for them to find their way in shops with affordable prices.\n\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-585 size-large\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/13499801_10209795966801884_753748227_o-768x1024.jpg\" alt=\"13499801_10209795966801884_753748227_o\" width=\"700\" height=\"933\" />\n\nWe understood that there was a genuine need for our project when one of the women told us that she had been starving for two days in a raw because she was not able to guide herself in the city. With the guidance of our supervisors we created some forms that consisted of the goods that the refugees need. We included the prices and the description of the goods and also detailed directions of how to reach the shop from the refugee center. After that, we visited the shops and filled in the forms. We managed to collect a significantly big amount of data that will be included in the guide.Finally we met a group of university students that introduced us to their initiative web platform where refuges can find guidance in many areas such as healthcare and shopping.\n\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-586 size-large\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/13509764_10209795966961888_1434780437_o-1024x768.jpg\" alt=\"13509764_10209795966961888_1434780437_o\" width=\"700\" height=\"525\" />\n\nThey invited us to upload the information that we have collected in the area of shopping so that more refugees have access into it. Although the project did not work as we expected due to some complications in communication and organization inside our group and with our contacts, we discovered in which areas we should improve and now we all feel more prepared and experienced for our next project. Our project is strongly interrelated with the UWC values and missions as each member of the group experienced a personal challenge, there was celebration of difference and intercultural understanding and we tried to be as environmentally sustainable as possible.\n\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-587 size-large\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/image1-1-1024x768.jpg\" alt=\"image1 (1)\" width=\"700\" height=\"525\" />\n\n-By Sofia Iris Kormpaki, Veronica Bejm Franco, Mesut Caliskan, Jacob Elton, Len Tha Lang, Dechen Zangmo, Cami Lindo, Oumaima Rhalem', 'Refugee welcome guide', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '584-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-06-23 09:33:14', '2017-06-23 09:33:14', '', 584, 'http://localhost/project_week/2017/06/23/584-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(794, 1, '2017-06-23 09:34:44', '2017-06-23 09:34:44', 'This past May break, the WinBin project week team set about on their project of bringing about positive environmental change, one bin at a time. Colin, Daan, Martijn, Tom, Cato, Elias and I (Ofek) were all motivated and excited to start this short week of building and creating recycling bins to be placed around the school. The idea behind WinBin was for us to plan and initiate our own project week of making bins after we realized there was a distinct lack of places within school where recyclable trash could be thrown away. We were all aware of the global importance of recycling, and were determined to do our bit on the fight against global warming. After recognizing this issue within the school community, we set about to try and change it by implementing Colin’s “green bin” idea from last year all around the school. Colin had designed and made a recycling bin during a Design Technology class last year, and we were planning on using its design during our Project week. Before the May break, we all consistently met and came together to discuss what exactly our action plan would be, as we wanted to ensure we made full use of the time we had. During these meetings, and after much discussion and collaborative work, we created the following vague action plan for us to follow.\n\n<strong>Day 1:</strong> Spend most of the day going to GAMMA and selecting/finding wood. After this is completed will return to school and spend the rest of the day cutting everything down to the correct dimensions. Goal of day: Get all pieces ready for assembly tomorrow.\n<strong>Day 2:</strong> We will start assembling the first bin today. This will probably take till about lunch. Afterwards we will apply the first (base) layer of paint to bin, so that we can divide roles tomorrow.\n\n<strong>Day 3:</strong> Apply first layer of colour paint to the bin. While this dries we will start construction and assembly of both the second and third bin.\n<strong>Day 4:</strong> Apply second layer of paint to first bin, and base layer to bins 2 and 3. Complete construction of the two remaining bins and alternate between applying paint layers. Additionally, file down all the bins and wood to be smooth before display. Clean-up all the mess.\nIn reality we were able to follow this plan somewhat, though at times we slightly deviated from it. This was the first time many of us were creating and designing something of this scale, and as such it took a while for us to fully develop and learn the necessary skills. Also, by bins 2 and 3 we were able to learn from mistakes made in the construction of bin 1, allowing for us to complete them quicker than expected.\n\nOverall, we all learned valuable lessons from this project week experience, ranging from practical skills to lessons on the importance recycling. We were all able to enjoy this week, and are all extremely proud of the end result. We really think these bins will bring about positive change to the school, and are excited to see them in use.\n- WinBin team 2016\n\n[gallery size=\"medium\" ids=\"568,567,566,565,564,562\"]\n\n&nbsp;', 'Win Bin Maastricht', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '553-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-06-23 09:34:44', '2017-06-23 09:34:44', '', 553, 'http://localhost/project_week/2017/06/23/553-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(795, 1, '2017-06-23 09:34:53', '2017-06-23 09:34:53', '<b>What did we do?</b>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For our project week, we decided to explore the country that suffered massacres and war crimes not longer than one and a half decades ago. Not only did the numerous colonizations and invasions in history have an impact on the country’s later developments, but up to this day it is still not internationally recognised as an independent country where the inhabitants still have to bear the ongoing conflicts between itself and its bordering countries. Our team was: Diona (Kosovo), Alon (Israel), JV (Philippines), Victoria (Bolivia), and Lorenzo (French/Italian). We all decided to choose Kosovo as the destination, precisely because of this historical background, which fascinated us. It was a really long trip to get there, we left early on April 28th and arrived to Pristina (Kosovo’s capital) by dawn next morning.  We volunteered with an NGO called “The Ideas Partnership” is a quite new organization founded by young kosovars, and what they do is that they gather volunteers to tackle education, promoting the preservation of cultural heritage and facing environmental challenges in Kosovo and the region, without political or religious affiliation.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">On the first day, we went Janjeva, a small town hiding in hills somewhere in the centre of Kosovo. Janjeva is a place whose unusually diverse cultural history can still be heard in the different languages spoken in its winding dusty streets, and in the wood, plaster and stone of the buildings. There, along with other volunteers, we prepared creativity classes for 2 different groups of children, guiding them through their drawings. It was a bit difficult to communicate with them, as only Diona spoke the language, but nevertheless, their warm spirit allowed is in the end, to make this sharing a memorable experience. We did this 2 other times, as well as English lessons.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Ideas Partnership doesn’t work on Sundays nor Labor Day, as the children attend to this extra learning opportunities right after their normal school hours, so in these two days we went a bit farther, and took a day off to Diona’s hometown Gjakova, were we walked around, met friends and family, and visited a post-war memorial of the victims. Once we got back to action, we went to Fushë Kosova, which is another section of the NGO’s program. Fushë Kosova is perhaps five miles away from the centre of Pristina. Families there are trying to live in single rooms on 60 hours a month, each and one of them with different and sadder stories; children who don’t go to school because they lack shoes and proper clothes, children who have limited access to basic education, etc. The employment of the majority is going through bins for scrap metal to sell for a few cents, and children begging in the streets. There we took lead of the English classes and the reading program. We were separated in different groups which were divided by age and proficiency in English, but these activities were only present in of the days. During the last day we took part of the creativity day, where we shared facts and legends of our own cultures, and learned about theirs. This last one, was very successful and one could see the joy around everybody, specially when they had to guess our countries and got it right (only once). Fushë Kosova also supports the Changemakers, which is a group of community members who want to improve their community themselves by organizing clean-up campaigns, and even took initiative in the creation of a kindergarten. The Changemakers group was specifically interesting to see, as a until-now-successful social entrepreneurship project.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Once our service days came to an end, we took those last 2 days to travel a bit more. We went to Prizren, an astonishingly beautiful old city, with a huge influence from the Ottoman Empire. We visited the fortress, hiked a bit, ate delicious traditional dishes. All team members agreed that our stay in Prizren was very relaxing, and brought us more together as a group. On the last day, we went to Gjakova again, and did some for walking. That same night, we took a taxi to Skopje  (Macedonia), catched our plane to Charleroi and returned to campus. It was a really nice experience that all of us will remember for a long time.</span>\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">PW Quote: “omg! This is so cheap!”</span>\n\n[gallery size=\"large\" ids=\"543,544,547,548,549,550,551,546,545\"]', 'Project Week in Kosovo', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '542-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-06-23 09:34:53', '2017-06-23 09:34:53', '', 542, 'http://localhost/project_week/2017/06/23/542-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
