(796, 1, '2017-06-23 09:35:02', '2017-06-23 09:35:02', '<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">We are a group of 6 girls: Chiara from Italy; Emi from Malaysia; Hana from Japan; Hellen from Eritrea and Sudan; Jana from Germany and Len from Myanmar. Our project was to investigate the social impact of the Berlin Wall. Throughout our project week we went to museums, got to know the city and had meaningful interviews with people on this issue. Due to the different backgrounds we are from, each one of us had different perspectives. We would sit and share our feelings each day, and it gave us the opportunity to reach a more complete understanding of our research.</span>\n\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/berlin2.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-539\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-539 size-full\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/berlin2.png\" alt=\"berlin2\" width=\"664\" height=\"441\" /></a>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Day 1 : On the first day, we went to the Deutsches Historisches museum, where we learnt about Germany before and after the World Wars. The next museum is the DDR museum. We observed the impact of the Wall, the ruling parties, personal stories, and ideologies from both East and West Germany at that time by using both primary and secondary resources available there.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Day 2:  At the Deutsches Technik, we saw a wide variety of technologies that brought Germany to its current shape such as weaving machines, boats, planes and cars.  In the computer section, we learned that computer skills were developing in the US during the separation of Berlin, so we could imagine the more developed life in the West side than the East.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Jewish museum showed us the history of their people, culture and religion starting from when Jewish religion started.  However, it wasn’t only about the beautiful culture.  We also saw the friction between Germans due to the differences in their religion.  The unique atmosphere of the museum\'s architecture stimulated our imagination.  </span>\n\n<strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Day 3: We visited the East Side Gallery and the German Resistance Memorial. The East Side Gallery is a kilometer of the Berlin Wall where art pieces have been drawn. There were creative drawings depicting the political and social issues. We saw how the Berlin Wall looked like and how the two sides were separated. Then, we went to the German Resistance Memorial. This was a memorial about the Berlin Wall and included stories of the people that lived at that time and their attempts of crossing the wall. Some succeeded and others were killed while trying to cross the wall. Around 138 people were killed trying to cross from the East to the West. They crossed because life was easier and there was more freedom in the west than in the East.</span></strong>\n\nDay 4: We conducted interviews with some locals and tourists on their knowledge and views about the Wall. We decided to go to the Tiergarten Park and approach people to ask questions. Some of the questions were:\n<ul>\n	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">What are your views on the Berlin Wall?</span></li>\n	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Were you taught anything about the Berlin Wall when you were still in school? If so, what information were you given?</span></li>\n	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Do you see any difference between the East and West Berlin today?</span></li>\n	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Do you still feel the effects of the Wall today?</span></li>\n	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Some people still feel that the Wall should be present today, what do you think</span></li>\n</ul>\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">We have interviewed around 15 people in the park, and found some very interesting views and perspective. We asked whether they feel that the wall should still exist, we got very different answers where some people were against it, while some people felt that the wall could also be beneficial in terms of jobs, standard of living etc, as the people are taken care by the government.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Through this project, we were able to learn about the history of the Wall and the separation of Berlin. We learned greatly about the impact this had on society. With two very different government systems in East and West, people were treated very differently. People were separated from each other for 28 years. A whole generation of people developing very different political ideologies, beliefs and attitudes, as all east-west relations had been forcibly terminated. The consequences of this political and social division have left their marks on society to this day.  It was very interesting to see and hear first-hand the impact this had on the Berlin society through conducting interviews with people on different ages and visiting memorial sites and museums, which enabled us to experience the issue in a much more authentic way.</span>\n\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/berlin.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-538\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-538 size-full\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/berlin.png\" alt=\"berlin\" width=\"662\" height=\"374\" /></a>', 'Berlin Wall', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '537-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-06-23 09:35:02', '2017-06-23 09:35:02', '', 537, 'http://localhost/project_week/2017/06/23/537-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(797, 1, '2017-06-23 09:35:14', '2017-06-23 09:35:14', '<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For my project week I had worked at Aalborgs Fosvars og Garnisons musuem, which is a museum about world war 2 in Denmark, where mostly volunteers worked. I had worked there for 4 days throughout the May break from 10:00am to 15:00pm each day. At first it was a new experience because I had never worked in Denmark before and to be honest was a bit nervous due to my lack of having spoken Danish in a long time. However it all went well once I got used to things. On the first day it was a bit awkward as they did not exactly have everything thought through and did not know what they wanted me to do. So on the first day I was set to clean and wash the cabinets and display cases that were there. This was not as boring as it actually sounds because I was able to listen to music and explore the events that had occurred throughout Denmark during World War 2. So it was also an educational project week for me. The second and third day I was set to vacuum the area and also clean again, once again getting a detailed look at things I could do. However on the third day I was able to get a free tour of the exhibits and learnt quite a lot. I was able to gain a better understanding of what they actually do and have there and made me glad to see that I am helping out. I was also able to spread a lot of information about UWC since they all were surprised as to me living in Holland and why I was doing service there. The people who were there were very generous. They said that I could take as many breaks as I wanted to and for lunch I could take a soda. They were also very interesting and had worked there for most of their life. On the fourth day I was putting price tags on the goods that they were selling which varied but also had the chance to fix some of the flash lights their which were broken. This was actually a really fun experience because I’ve always had a passion for being able to fix something which is supposed to be broken. I had fixed most of the flashlights although some were beyond fixing. When discussing the project week as a whole I think that it was a very fun experience and would advise other people to do it since it is simple, educational and a fun experience. However I would advise people to do it in a group as it can tend to get quite a bit lonely when doing it by yourself. If you are fond of history I would advise it. I really enjoyed myself and met new people, learnt new cleaning skills and speaking skills as well and social behavior as a whole. This project week was a generally good experience for me and the people I helped. </span>\n\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/Denmark.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-534\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-534 size-full\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/Denmark.png\" alt=\"Denmark\" width=\"555\" height=\"372\" /></a> <a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/denmark2.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-535\"><img class=\"wp-image-535 size-full aligncenter\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/denmark2.png\" alt=\"denmark2\" width=\"662\" height=\"439\" /></a>', 'Denmark WWII Museum', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '533-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-06-23 09:35:14', '2017-06-23 09:35:14', '', 533, 'http://localhost/project_week/2017/06/23/533-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(798, 1, '2017-06-23 09:35:28', '2017-06-23 09:35:28', 'The project week ‘In Search of Impressionist Eyes’ was aimed to researching French impressionists in the 19th and 20th century in Paris. The Project had a particular focus on Claude Monet, who is often considered to be the father of impressionism. The reason for this project was to investigate how this group of people managed to change the art culture so drastically, and what difficulties they encountered along the way.\n\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/paris.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-524\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-524 size-full\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/paris.jpg\" alt=\"paris\" width=\"1000\" height=\"667\" /></a>\n\nTo start my project and introduce myself to Claude Monet, I went straight to the Marmottan museum. This museum has a permanent exposition dedicated to Monet and contains some of his artworks from various points in his life. This first experience was key to gathering my first impressions of the impressionist movement and Monet’s life, later on I frequently went back to add to the things I noticed on this first visit.\nAfter the first introduction, I moved on to the D’Orsay museum. This second visit included many other impressionist artists of Monet’s time period who lived in France. Also, I was able to see some paintings from impressionists from other countries like Van Gogh, and was able to compare his artworks with the ones I had previously seen. It would be a great extension to this project week to research Van Gogh and Dutch impressionists to see the full impact that the French impressionists had and the differences between the two movements.\n\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/paris7.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-530\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-530 size-full\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/paris7.jpg\" alt=\"paris7\" width=\"640\" height=\"480\" /></a>\n\nOn the second day I visited the Louvre museum, with the objective of seeing the impressionist exhibition of artists in the late 19<sup>th</sup> century, and early 20<sup>th</sup> century. Unfortunately that particular exhibition was closed, along with a few others due to working strike. Even though this obstacle came along, I visited the museum to see the kinds of artistic movements that were present in the past and to get an idea of where exactly impressionism was shifting from\n\nAfter the visit at the Louvre museum, I visited the Orangerie. A museum dedicated and built around Monet’s giant water lilies oil on canvases. The sight of these enormous paintings was breath taking for me, and it was possible for me to understand the severeness of Monet’s sight condition that had manifested towards the end of his life. Monet had to rely on creating enormous paintings since he could no longer see clearly up close.\n\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/paris2.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-525\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-525 size-full\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/paris2.jpg\" alt=\"paris2\" width=\"640\" height=\"480\" /></a>\n\n&nbsp;\n\nAfter seeing an overview of Monet’s painting life and the one of his painter friends, I went to visit the Renoir Gardens in the area of Mon Matre. This area of Paris was and still is known to be a common place where artists lived and met up. During the time I visited, the artists in the area were exposing their artworks in the streets. Experiencing the atmosphere in which Impressionist artists grew and lived was very enriching and mind opening; I had to note that it is important to be surrounded by a community that supports you and in which you feel comfortable to do what you believe in.\n\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/paris3.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-526\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-526 size-full\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/paris3.jpg\" alt=\"paris3\" width=\"640\" height=\"480\" /></a>\n\nThe very last day, to get the final glimpses at Monet’s life, I visited his house in Giverny, where he spent the last years of his life, and created his famous water lily oil on canvases. During these last years Monet’s eyesight worsened with the years, but every time he was able to find ways to improve it he would paint as much as he could to use the full potential of his temporary cure. Visiting his house gave me an insight into what kind of person he was, one that would not simply stop doing what he loved because of old age or other restrictions, he was also known to sit through the coldest and the hottest of days to paint his heart out on canvas before the moment he was trying to capture would disappear. I think the last visit to his house and gardens were a perfect closing to the project week, that left me reflecting on the visit long after it was over.\n\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/paris5.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-528\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-528 size-full\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/paris5.jpg\" alt=\"paris5\" width=\"1000\" height=\"688\" /></a> <a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/paris6.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-529\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-529 size-full\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/paris6.jpg\" alt=\"paris6\" width=\"1000\" height=\"667\" /></a>', 'In Search of Impressionist Eyes - Paris', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '523-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-06-23 09:35:28', '2017-06-23 09:35:28', '', 523, 'http://localhost/project_week/2017/06/23/523-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(799, 1, '2017-06-23 09:35:40', '2017-06-23 09:35:40', '<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/nuclear.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-621\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-621\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/nuclear.jpg\" alt=\"nuclear\" width=\"1052\" height=\"790\" /></a>\n\nI wouldn’t say going to Palestine has particularly ever been on my bucket list, nor did I ever stop to think that it would be possible to travel such a ‘conflict area’. Growing up in an Arab (Moroccan) family, the Israeli-Palestinian conflict has always been quite present in my life, either on the news or in discussions during family events. This has, unsurprisingly, made me very biased in favor of Palestine.  The also biased Western media coverage of the conflict has led to many people viewing Palestine as a country in perpetual conflict and war, full of Hamas terrorists throwing rocks and stabbing civilians. So when Hannah once was telling me about her friend Obada who lived in Palestine and who she would love to visit in the future, I wasn’t very serious when I proposed to go during May break. Hannah (Netherlands), on the other hand, was already excited and after I asked my parents, who very surprisingly were much easier to convince than I could have ever expected, it was pretty much a set deal (although convincing the school was a bit more difficult). Isabella (Canada) and Asbjorn (Denmark) joined us, and after a few weeks packed with intense preparations (airport-interrogations simulations and a risk assessment of 20 pages long), I promised my parents a few dozen times to be very careful and we boarded on our flight to Israel.\n\nTel Aviv welcomed us with open arms, a dust storm and 36 degrees Celsius.  When we arrived at the airport, we were all quite nervous as we had heard stories about people being denied entry to Israel for ridiculous reasons such as seeming to be a political activist or having an Arab-sounding last name. The passport control went easier than we expected, although they were a bit hesitant with me, asking me questions about my family’s background and if I had any acquaintance in Palestine. That same night we were staying over at Hila’s place, one of Asbjorn’s childhood friends. They were very shocked to hear that we came to visit the West Bank rather than the usual Israeli tourist attractions.\n\nWe had an interesting discussion at 4.30 am in their kitchen while eating hummus with crackers (“Actually it’s Passover and they’re not selling bread in the stores.. But we’re not religious so we stocked in some bread last week”). When we were heading off to Jerusalem the following morning, Hila’s mother saw the title of our tour guide (titled ‘Israel and the Palestinian territories), and all of a sudden she got very upset, claiming that ‘the title gave the illusion that there was such a thing as Palestine’. She then went on to explain the case for the Israelis, stating that this was the only place they had in the world, and if they lost the war, they had nowhere to go whereas there ‘were so many Arab countries for them to go to’. Hila’s mom then said how ‘they’ (it was always ‘they’ or ‘those Arabs’, never ‘Palestinians’) didn’t want peace, how they educated their children to be terrorists and praised violence. As we didn’t quite know how to start arguing with such deep-rooted beliefs in front of an airport, we decided to just nod and leave it to what it was.<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/nuclear2.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-622\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-622\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/nuclear2.jpg\" alt=\"nuclear2\" width=\"760\" height=\"571\" /></a> <a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/nuclear3.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-623\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-623\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/nuclear3.jpg\" alt=\"nuclear3\" width=\"750\" height=\"563\" /></a>', 'Palestine', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '620-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-06-23 09:35:40', '2017-06-23 09:35:40', '', 620, 'http://localhost/project_week/2017/06/23/620-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(800, 1, '2017-06-23 09:36:26', '2017-06-23 09:36:26', 'For our project week we endeavored to the great lands of Scandinavia to face the cold winds and grey skies. Actually it wasn\'t that cold and we were graced with a few days of sun. We worked with an organization in Sweden called Mosaik a branch of a larger organisation called Students for Christ Europe (SFC Europe). This is in an organization leading to broaden discussions about faith, our beliefs and why we believe. One of our goals was to reach out to students in Malmo on their views of faith particularly Christianity and get their opinions on what role religion has in Sweden. In addition, though Sweden can be identified as a prosperous country the region we went to still faces some degree of poverty. This is especially faced by the Romani people. So with the church we volunteered at a homeless shelter where we helped to prepare meals and take care of other necessities such as making the beds and cleaning up. The people staying there usually pay a small fee of less than 2 euros which includes a night stay, 3 meals and other utilities. The church aims to help as many homeless people but does this with a fee as to give the people a sense of responsibility, dignity and a reward for their hard work.\n\nDuring our project week we decided to try and achieve the following goals:\n<ol>\n	<li>Organize activities outside the campus.\nThe activities that we took part in were not completely organized by us alone, as most of the work we did was in collaboration with other organizations. However we took initiative and made clear as to what and how we would be doing. For example when we volunteered at the homeless shelter. The work itself was not organized by us but we made contact and were willing to take part.</li>\n	<li>Explore a new country and culture.\nAfter we had completed our service and during our breaks we were able to converse with the local people whom we were working with. This allowed us to get an understanding of the culture from a primary source. Also, on our final night, we were hosted by a resident family. During our time there we learned much about the culture and history of that area. Not only did we chat with locals but we also made time for exploring the city and experience the area. We spent many hours walking the city and familiarizing ourselves with our environment</li>\n	<li>Design and pursue a student-led project.\nThe trip and project were organized by ourselves in collaboration with the organization that we were assisting. Also, we lead ourselves during the project. At times working with the organization and at time our own work.</li>\n	<li>Improve your organization, communication and collaboration skills.\nOur trip was great organization experience as it allowed us to work without relying on an adult. Also our communication and collaboration between the group and with third parties improved. We were able to work together as a group without any mishaps or conflict.</li>\n	<li>Get to know more about yourself and your group.\nTogether as a group we had an amazing time and learned much about each other. This was done late at night chatting but also during our service times and during planning. Even interacting with the third party people taught us something about how we interacted with people away from home and the UWC.</li>\n	<li>Share and spread the UWC mission and values.\nWhile doing our service we were often asked as to why we came and why we were helping. Dutifully we told them about the UWC and its mission. People responded positively to this and we’re excited that such a mission exists. People were also impressed that such student led initiatives existed.</li>\n	<li>Achieve a positive (social) change.\nThe work we did helping at the homeless shelter created a more positive environment not only through helping with the labor, but also through encouragement and motivation.</li>\n</ol>\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/Capture-6.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-488\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-488 size-full\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/Capture-6.png\" alt=\"Capture\" width=\"684\" height=\"381\" /></a>\n\n[spacer height=\"20px\"]We decided to join the project for a number of reasons. Firstly all of us were very interested in volunteering at the homeless shelter and interested to serve in any way that we could as at first it was shock that this issue existed in a scandinavian country. In addition this was a unique project, that none of us had never done. We were all extremely anxious to talk about our own beliefs and opinions to strangers but wanted to challenge ourselves, especially by going to another country.\n\n[spacer height=\"20px\"]Even after all this said one might still ask: ‘Still what made your PW so important? How did your PW even link to the UWC mission and values? Was it any use to go, really?’\n\n[spacer height=\"20px\"]In congruence with all the numerous, so-true points mentioned above, during our project week we also learned more about our Christian faith. This was really important to us for as students in the UWC community we would like to contribute to the diversity in faith by knowing more about our actual spiritual beliefs, so that we are able to share those ideas. In the UWC mission it states that we must strive to reach ‘the celebration of difference’, and by going on this project week we added more difference to be celebrated in our mainly secular school.\n\n[spacer height=\"20px\"]On our project week we did not only further establish Jesus’ love for us, what we also did was serve at a homeless shelter. The security guard on the first day told us to speak of the shelter to the public in discretion in order to avoid complaints from locals about how homeless people get everything for free from the government. This not only incorrect opinion in the case of the homeless shelter we worked at since they do pay a fee of 15 krona for a bed, a grooming packet, dinner and breakfast, is unfortunately the mentality some have towards those with no money. We didn’t even know that it wasn’t for free either but through this experience we got more informed and therefore less biased, which is also what UWC aims to instill in us.\n\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/Capture-7.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-489\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-489 size-full\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/Capture-7.png\" alt=\"Capture\" width=\"649\" height=\"833\" /></a>\n\n[spacer height=\"20px\"]As a team we looked out for each other even if it just meant encouraging words on our long walks, making sure everybody woke up on time or attempting to relieving another’s blister pain through well- meant footwear advice. The project week was all great way to emulate the ‘mutual responsibility and respect’ part of the UWC mission statement. Furthermore, when making food for the homeless we had to be very hygienic and respectful by wearing gloves and washing our hands. It is often very easy to bend the rules and not care because no one would know so you wouldn\'t get caught but we practiced our integrity well and out of respect for the shelter seekers, we handled their food appropriately.\n\n[spacer height=\"20px\"]From the project week our friendships grew stronger, we got a taster of what being a responsible young adult is like in the ‘real world’ away from the protection of our safe, idealistically minded UWC community.\n\n[spacer height=\"20px\"]All this seems pretty worthwhile to us.', 'Sweden', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '486-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-06-23 09:36:26', '2017-06-23 09:36:26', '', 486, 'http://localhost/project_week/2017/06/23/486-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(801, 1, '2017-06-23 09:36:36', '2017-06-23 09:36:36', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">by Ulises, Oumaima, Ceri, Charlotte, Valeria, Martin, Pietro, Sofia, Aya and Kathleen</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">[spacer height=\"20px\"]We just arrived at Weez airport in Dusseldorf it is only 4:20 and we have to wait until 9 in order to take our flight to Fez, Morocco. An atmosphere of excitement covers our team since we left campus. Another country, another continent, another culture is just three hours and a half from us.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">[spacer height=\"20px\"]We just arrived in <strong>Fez</strong>, Morocco. The weather was surprisingly fresh, with a lot of dry wind. The effects of globalization could be seen since the moment we landed because the airport was just renovated and the installations where incredibly well designed. Furthermore, as we move along the city with the help of Aya’s parents, the effect of globalization could be seen more and more. Houses, large buildings were replacing the olive plantations in the surroundings of Fez.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/Capture-4.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-411\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-411 size-full\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/Capture-4.png\" alt=\"Capture\" width=\"605\" height=\"452\" /></a></p>\n\n<h2 style=\"text-align: justify;\">[spacer height=\"20px\"]Our first Moroccan breakfast!</h2>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Sadly not all of us eat meat! However the ones we do, it was amazing! Eggs with a different kind of meat, “man” (no idea how it is spelled but it was heavenly delicious), some other sweet pieces of bread that were just full of taste. The environment around the restaurant was busier than our usual Maastricht but with a calm environment. A ride of at least three hours was ahead of us, we went through Rabat without stopping just to barely see it. <strong>Casablanca</strong> was our main goal by this day, however in our way we encountered with beautiful deserted landscapes that for many of us were totally new. Morocco is incredibly huge! So much free land.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">We discover the preference of Oumaima towards Indians! But we are going to keep the lucky one anonymously!</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">[spacer height=\"20px\"]As soon as we arrived at Aya’s house in Casablanca, the dinner was waiting for us! Well, we thought it was the dinner but it was the gate that is before the dinner. And the dinner was a combination of different salads, olives, chicken, beef which was perfectly combined. We all sleep really well that night! The first Breakfast! Pancakes, tangerines, bread, milk, amlo and more! Was just wonderful! Afterwards, we went to the French school, however, our entrance was not permitted because they were afraid of terrorist attacks. (If like a Mexican a Salvadoran, or even a girl from Hong Kong will attack) However, we observed how the impact of the globalization affected the areas surrounding the French school.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">[spacer height=\"20px\"]We visited the Mosque Hassan II, one of the biggest in the whole world. We had the chance to visit inside of it. The amount of money that the king had to put on it has to be incredibly huge! Also, we had the chance to visit the biggest mall in the whole continent of Africa. An aquarium was waiting for us just in the middle of the mall.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">[spacer height=\"20px\"]Hammam! The boys and the hammam got along pretty well! Hammam was a kind of spa where you get scrubbed in a warm room. The guys slept really well! After we all ate real couscous!</p>\n\n<h2 style=\"text-align: justify;\">[spacer height=\"20px\"]On our way to Marrakech!</h2>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">We just took the train to <b>Marrakesh</b>! The train was surprisingly well maintained. The impact of globalization had reached almost everywhere but not everyone. The development of the city of Marrakesh is incredibly high, however not everybody has the access to all of this new resources. In Marrakesh, we had the chance to discuss this and another type of problems with other teenagers. We had the chance to discuss the state of the monarchy is nowadays and how this and external factors affect the society as a whole. A lack of opportunities and a sense of censorship surrounds the youth we talked to, problems that are common everywhere else but that its roots are well into the ground, in such a way that is hard to find a solution.</p>\n<a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/Capture-5.png\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-412\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-412 size-full\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/Capture-5.png\" alt=\"Capture\" width=\"420\" height=\"558\" /></a>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Marrakesh we had the chance to visit characteristic market which makes this city famous worldwide. A number of colors and different artifacts is characteristic of this place. Scarfs, food, seafood, spices anything you want can be found there. Morocco ends up being a country where all our expectations were and were not right at the same time. We experimented hospitality to the fullest from Aya’s parents, we felt morocco as a living organism made up of great people which are always moving, working, dancing, cooking, singing, playing all the time. Morocco ends up being for most of us the trigger for a paradigm shift towards our stereotypes. Morocco for project week, was a wise decision, not only for the particular environment but also for the people and the conversations we had with them. It is different to read about a country’s situation than experiencing it. We left Morocco with a feeling of hearts and flowers, with the aim to go back and actually immerse ourselves within their culture.</p>', 'Morocco', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '410-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-06-23 09:36:36', '2017-06-23 09:36:36', '', 410, 'http://localhost/project_week/2017/06/23/410-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(802, 1, '2017-06-23 09:36:49', '2017-06-23 09:36:49', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><strong>Information about organizations:</strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><strong><u>Syrian Education Commission</u></strong>:This is a non-profit, non-political civil society organization that is specialized in the educational process in all its stages. It takes cares of the Syrian students by monitoring and seeking solutions for them through values such as teamwork, originality and modernity, credibility and transparency and professional standards. They have created many projects but the one that we visited was the “Project of Dropout Pupils”, which consists in establishing centers in Turkey for educating and rehabilitating students who have been deprived of education in order to prevent them from wandering in the streets and getting lost in the mazes of ignorance and terrorism. </span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><u><strong>[spacer height=\"20px\"]ASAM (Istanbul’s unit)</strong>:</u> The Association for Solidarity with Asylum Seekers and Migrants (ASAM) was established in Ankara on December 22, 1995 as a non-profit and non-governmental organization. The primary goal of ASAM is to create solutions to the problems that refugees and asylum seekers encounter in Turkey, to help them to fulfill their primary needs and to support them to provide access for fundamental rights and services. ASAM provides services to refugees and asylum seekers without discrimination on the grounds of language, religion, sex, race, sexual orientation and political ideology.(Veronica, UWCM\'17)</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW12.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-383\"><img class=\"wp-image-383 size-large aligncenter\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW12-1024x683.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px\" srcset=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW12-300x200.jpg 300w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW12-768x512.jpg 768w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW12-1024x683.jpg 1024w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW12-272x182.jpg 272w\" alt=\"PW12\" width=\"700\" height=\"467\" /></a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW14.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-381\"><img class=\"wp-image-381 size-large aligncenter\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW14-1024x576.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px\" srcset=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW14-300x169.jpg 300w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW14-768x432.jpg 768w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW14-1024x576.jpg 1024w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW14.jpg 1334w\" alt=\"PW14\" width=\"700\" height=\"394\" /></a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><strong>[spacer height=\"20px\"]Why this project week?</strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">We chose this project week for couple of reasons. The first one is the activity, which is helping Syrian refugees. As we all know, many Syrians left their country, which is in a situation of a brutal civil war, in order to start their life again. We felt obligated to help them, and especially the kids, who are the next generation. Another reason is the location. Many people assume that Turkey is not a safe place because of what they hear in the media. We wanted to go there in order to see what Turkey is really is, and it turned out to be one of the most welcoming places we have ever been to! Despite the media, Turkey is safe, Istanbul is safe, and it was important to prove that.</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">(Achiad, UWCM’16)</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW11.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-384\"><img class=\"wp-image-384 size-large aligncenter\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW11-1024x576.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px\" srcset=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW11-300x169.jpg 300w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW11-768x432.jpg 768w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW11-1024x576.jpg 1024w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW11.jpg 1334w\" alt=\"PW11\" width=\"700\" height=\"394\" /></a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><strong>[spacer height=\"20px\"]One of our days: </strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Thursday 11th of February - </span><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Day four.</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #333333;\">This day was our second day in the organisation “Al Asam”. We left our apartment that is in the area of Sultan Ahmet at approximately 9 o\'clock to go to Karaköy. From that point we had to walk more than one hour. It was really difficult because the city is like a mountain and we do need to climb especially the way we had taken that day. We arrived to the organisation at around 10 and there was a Turkish lesson for the children (3 to 8 years old). We joined the lesson and helped the children with memorizing exercise. After the end of the lesson we had a lot of fun activities with them and this was the most important and enjoying moment of the journey. At 3 o\'clock the second group of students came. They were mainly teenagers and with a highest age of 15. The day before we have gone with them near to the sea for their photography lesson. That day they had hip hop dance and singing lesson. The teachers were really professional and they danced very well. We also joined the dance lesson. And we had fun. The day before during the way to the sea they have taught us some Arabic and we taught them our first languages. At the end of the dance lesson was the singing lesson. Each of the teenagers had their own lyrics that they sing to express what they cannot say through music. We also participated to that lesson by doing random freestyle on a bit. At the end of the day we had an exchanges of addresses with them to keep being in touch.</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">(Naimatou, UWCM’17)</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW15.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-380\"><img class=\"wp-image-380 size-large aligncenter\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW15-1024x681.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px\" srcset=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW15-300x200.jpg 300w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW15-768x511.jpg 768w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW15-1024x681.jpg 1024w\" alt=\"PW15\" width=\"700\" height=\"466\" /></a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><strong>[spacer height=\"20px\"]Our objectives :</strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Our learning goals and objectives are to build project planning skills through the organization of the project week, build communication skills through the contact with Syrian organizations, become more aware of the situation of the Syrian children in foreign countries and have an impact on them through our own effort. During the project week in Istanbul we achieved our learning goals and objectives fully. Meanwhile, we planned the trip in Turkey entirely on our own: we booked the flight tickets, apartments and navigated ourselves to different locations, while everything went on smoothly. Also, we had a very good time with both organizations we worked with. We contacted them beforehand and arrived on time. They were very welcoming and there was no miscommunication within the process. Sitting together with Syrian kids from different age groups in the same room, we had a great opportunity to interact with them closely and understand them better. Although there were huge language barriers among us, as we couldn’t speak arabic nor turkish, they didn’t stop us from being friends with those innocent, cheerful kids. At the end of the day we became from very close to one another and too hard to say goodbye. However, despite the fact that we enjoyed a lot working with the organization, we did identify several problems and difficult that the Syrian refugees encountered. A lot of them are suffering from poverty, because of their family inability to make a living, the kids themselves have to work by selling tissues to pedestrians. Though the organizations provide basic education for them, they don’t have money for textbooks and the basic educational resources. For them education is a luxury. We felt very sad about that and through the speech we gave them, and all the games we played with them, we hoped that they would never give up their hope and dreams and thrive with the help of education.</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">(Nina, UWCM’17)</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW17.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-378\"><img class=\"wp-image-378 size-large aligncenter\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW17-1024x681.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px\" srcset=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW17-300x200.jpg 300w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW17-768x511.jpg 768w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW17-1024x681.jpg 1024w\" alt=\"PW17\" width=\"700\" height=\"466\" /></a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW18.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-377\"><img class=\"wp-image-377 size-large aligncenter\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW18-1024x681.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px\" srcset=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW18-300x200.jpg 300w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW18-768x511.jpg 768w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW18-1024x681.jpg 1024w\" alt=\"PW18\" width=\"700\" height=\"466\" /></a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><strong>[spacer height=\"20px\"]The importance of this Project Week :<em>                  </em></strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">We headed to Turkey to help with the syrian refugees. The trip there was a challenge, because a lot of us come from priviledged backgrounds. We learned that the world is far from ideal and that there is a long way to go. However we all believed that if we fight and if we taught the children to fight as well for everyone’s rights, the world will become a better place. Staying with the children was a personal challenge because of the language barrier, which was interesting because as much as we were different we were still able to comprehend each other and to build a special relationship. Also, dealing with children and seeing them facing a such situation where they flee from their home and have to find a way to survive in the street made us sad, angry and more compassionate towards the cause. But we were there, we showed them support and even if they were young and might not have ununderstood why we left so early, at least we made them smile and this wasn’t the kind of smiles you can see in Western Europe. These were pure smiles that you cannot immitate. As bad as their situation can be, you can still see the way they are interested by anything and the happiness they can share with you. I think this project week was definitely important for each of us in the sense that we directly saw what we used to hear on the TV, medias, internet and that it changed somehow our mind. We all come from different countries and for some of us, going in Turkey with such a different culture than where we are from was eye opening to the similarities and differences that western and eastern cultures can have. The fact that one paraguayan, one guatemalan, two french, one moroccan, one egyptian, one burkinabe, one israeli and one chinese show that it is possible to help and that it is not that complicated to help people different from us.</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">(Mathilde, UWCM’17)</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW16.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-379\"><img class=\"wp-image-379 size-large aligncenter\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW16-1024x681.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px\" srcset=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW16-300x200.jpg 300w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW16-768x511.jpg 768w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW16-1024x681.jpg 1024w\" alt=\"PW16\" width=\"700\" height=\"466\" /></a></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\">This project week lasted four days, but our actions won’t stop there. We come from all over the world and with this experience we can continue, at even bigger scales, to help</span>. <span style=\"color: #000000;\">The refugee crisis is not a joke and media don’t share everything, so it’s our own responsibility to decide whether or not we should try to save people who die or children who are losing their childhood</span>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW13.jpg\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-382\"><img class=\"wp-image-382 size-large\" src=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW13-1024x683.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px\" srcset=\"http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW13-300x200.jpg 300w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW13-768x512.jpg 768w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW13-1024x683.jpg 1024w, http://uwcmaastrichtimpact.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/PW13-272x182.jpg 272w\" alt=\"PW13\" width=\"700\" height=\"467\" /></a></p>', 'Istanbul, Turkey', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '376-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-06-23 09:36:49', '2017-06-23 09:36:49', '', 376, 'http://localhost/project_week/2017/06/23/376-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
